<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Cabinet Begins First Day in Berlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Together with his Foreign Minister
Joschka Fischer and other cabinet members, German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder formally began to govern the country in Berlin
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Returning from Italy after a summer holiday, Schroeder said it
was a "historical day" that Germany's political center had moved
to its old capital from the small city of Bonn beside the Rhine
River.
</P>
<P>
"I am lucky to be able to live in Berlin," he said in a
television interview.
</P>
<P>
Again, Schroeder thanked those who had made contributions to
German reunification that made its possible for him to live in
Berlin. The people he mentioned including the then French
President Francois Mitterrand, the then U.S. President George
Bush, and especially Schroeder's predecessor, then Chancellor
Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Almost 10 years after reunification and eight years after the
German parliament passed the bill of relocating its capital, most
parts of the country's ruling machine have found their sites in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The parliament and seven federal ministries, namely foreign,
transport, interior, justice, health, finance, and environment,
have begun their operations in succession. The other seven
ministries, the Defense Ministry being the most important among
them, will be left in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
But without a Chancellory in the capital, Schroeder will have
to locate his temporary residence in the building of former East
Germany's State Council until year 2000, with Fischer as the
neighbor. A new Chancellory, costing 465 million marks (252
million U.S. dollars), is now under construction near the famous
Reichstag building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
