<HEADLINE> Research Work on Female Genital Mutilation to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- There is need to intensify
research work on female genital mutilation (FGM) in Africa to help
abolish the inhuman practice, a professor said Monday in Ghana's
capital.
</P>
<P>
Ghana News Agency reported that professor Patrick Twumasi said
this at the opening ceremony of the three-day regional steering
group meeting on prevention of FGM, the first of its kind
organized by the World Health Organization (WHO) in collaboration
with Ghana's Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The meeting aims to identify the best practice for preventing
FGM, integrate them into national FGM prevention and management
programs and stimulate the formation of regional steering groups.
</P>
<P>
The practice of FGM is an obstacle to the attainment of good
health, development and human rights not only for its victims but
for all members of society, Twumasi said.
</P>
<P>
He said it has been estimated that more than 130 million girls
and women have undergone genital mutilation world-wide with two
million more at risk every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
