<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Concerned at Humanitarian Crisis in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday voiced its concerns about "the deteriorating humanitarian
situation" in Angola and called on the warring Angolan factions to
provide relief access to the internally displaced persons (IDPs)
in the southwestern African country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
Security Council, Martin Andjaba of Namibia, said, "Members of the
council remained extremely concerned about the deteriorating
humanitarian situation in Angola."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the council expressed concern at the low level of
response by donors to the humanitarian appeal for Angola," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the U.N. Security Council met in a
closed-door session to be briefed by Hedi Annabi, U.N. assistant
secretary-general for peacekeeping operations, Sergio Vieira de
Mello, undersecretary-general for humanitarian affairs, Catherine
Bertini, director of the World Food Program, and Carol Bellamy,
executive director of the United Nations Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
"They commended the efforts of the humanitarian agencies
operating in Angola in assisting the Angolan government to meet
the needs of IDPs," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the council welcomed the announcement by the
government of Angola for an Emergency Plan for Humanitarian
Assistance," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"They called on the government of Angola and in particular
UNITA (the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola)
to provide access to the internally displaced persons," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
At present, 2 million Angolans are living a precarious
existence, another 3 million completely inaccessible, with scarce
food and shelter, and large numbers of children at risk of death
if hostilities continue, a U.N. spokesman said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is planning to open a liaison office in
Angola to explore ways to restore peace in the country, six months
after the withdrawal of U.N. peacekeepers from the southwestern
African country.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has agreed to allow the new U.N.
office, which will set up links with security and civilian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
U.N. humanitarian operations have continued to be conducted in
the African country since the departure of the peacekeeping
forces.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations spent 10 years and millions of U.S. dollars
trying to bring peace to the African nation, where civil war broke
out soon after its 1975 independence from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
At present, fighting, population displacement, drought and
disease have wrought "exceptional food emergencies" in 16 African
countries with Angola hit hardest, the United Nations Food and
Agricultural Organization said in early August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
