<HEADLINE> Eaton's Share Drops Another 49 Cents Upon Insolvency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- T. Eaton Co. Ltd. suffered a drop
of 49 cents (about 0.33 U.S. dollars) to 36.5 cents (about 0.24
U.S. dollars) each share early Monday, CTV reported.
</P>
<P>
The once retailing icon of Canada announced Friday that it
plans to file for protection from its creditors Monday under the
Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act.
</P>
<P>
Key lenders of Canada's oldest institution of more than 130
years are negotiating to sell their debt of 170 million Canadian
dollars (about 114 million U.S. dollars) while the collapsing
retailer prepares to liquidate its 64-store chain's inventory this
week.
</P>
<P>
GE Capital Corp and two other U.S. finance companies are owed
the money by Eaton's, which has 30 days to come up with a plan to
carve up its assets and distribute the proceeds to its creditors,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Another 50 million Canadian dollars (about 33 million U.S.
dollars) were reported to be owed by such unsecured creditors as
clothing manufacturers, which are expected to receive little from
the remains of the money-losing retailer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
