<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Adds Misery to Quake-Hit Turks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Ozek family, which lost two
members in the killer quake last Tuesday, was subjected to more
miseries as a sudden downpour Monday battered their makeshift
tents on a lawn.
</P>
<P>
The 12 survivors of the family have been accommodated in four
small tents on a lawn about 100 meters from their crushed home in
the Guney Mahalle Tuprid Street in the hardest-hit Izmit, 70
kilometers southeast of Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
The tents became more crowed as the family had to move some of
what they thought valuable possessions, including a television and
a tape-recorder, into the tents.
</P>
<P>
A few pieces of wooden furniture, some kitchen utensils, a
cauldron of onions, two buckets of drinking water and a small gas
stove distributed by government relief workers had to be left in
the rain.
</P>
<P>
The Ozeks had to shift the doors of the tents to the lower side
of the sloping lawn so as to keep water outside.
</P>
<P>
The Ozeks were seen approaching a car stopping at the nearby
street to receive medicines and most needed items.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Nazmi, one of the personnel distributing aid items
around the car, said that they were from public hospitals in Izmit
and Istanbul and volunteers in the "Can I Help You" action for
distributing medicines and offering medical aid to victims.
</P>
<P>
The action involves 40 doctors and 10 cars, Nazmi said, adding
that they had been working on sites since Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Such medical teams from local hospitals and foreign countries
are travelling in the quake-hit areas to provide medical aid to
victims in tents
</P>
<P>
A powerful quake, measured at 7.4 degrees on the Richter
scale, hit western Turkey last Tuesday, killing at least 1,2134
people and injuring 33,000 others, with thousands more still
buried under the tangled concrete.
</P>
<P>
Monday's rain has posed another disaster for the quake
victims. Though it eased the choking dust and scorching heat that
dominated in the last few days, health experts fear that it might
help the spread of diseases. The possibility of an outbreak of
epidemic has been one of the major concerns for the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Health official are grappling with ways to curb possible
spread of diseases like typhoid fever, cholera and dysentery.
</P>
<P>
Officials were spraying disinfectant over stricken areas where
stench of corpses can be smelt in dust. They have also started
spreading purifying lime on rubble, roads and cemeteries. Water
purification tablets were being distributed in some regions.
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 people were left homeless and had to stay in
makeshift tents for the time being. As tents were not enough, some
rendered homeless still had to sleep in the open air. Seeking
shelters in the torrential rain, which is expected to last through
the coming days, is an even daunting task for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
