<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL -- With the hope getting slim for finding more people
alive under the rubble, the Turkish government is shifting its
priority to helping the hundreds of thousands of survivors
rendered homeless by last Tuesday's catastrophic earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government is convinced that it is to the benefit
of the surviving quake victims that the clearance of debris start
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Bulldozers and tracks are moving into more quake-hit sites to
haul away mountains of rubble, preparing for setting up more
makeshift tents and for future reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of an outbreak of epidemic is one of the major
concerns of the authorities. Health officials are grappling with
ways to block possible spread of diseases like typhoid fever,
cholera and dysentery. (BC-Turkey-Quake-Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said Monday
that Israel has agreed to release Palestinian prisoners in two
stages, the first batch in early September and the second on
October 8.
</P>
<P>
However, the two sides failed to reach agreement on the number
of prisoners to be released in each phase.
(BC-Palestinians-Israel-Prisoners)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' Defense Minister Yiannakis Chrysostomis
Monday tendered his resignation to President Glafcos Clerides "for
reasons of dignity and sensitivity."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists at the presidential palace after a
brief meeting with President Clerides, Chrysostomis said the
president accepted his resignation.
(BC-Cyprus-Defense Minister-Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators Monday reached
a deal on the construction of a seaport in Gaza and the opening of
a safe passage between Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The two issues are aspects of the Palestinian-Israeli Wye
Accord signed last October in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat told Israel Radio
that the two sides will accelerate talks to iron out difference on
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank, the major part of the
accord. (BC-Israel-Palestine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel on Monday decided to provide more medical
equipment for Turkey and help re-construct its communications
network severely damaged in a devastating earthquake last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a statement that it has decided to
dispatch two cargo planes to transport medicine and medical
equipment to Turkey in response to a request from the Turkish Red
Crescent.
</P>
<P>
Other measures included providing assistance in restoring
Turkey's battered communications network and organizing special
seminars both in Israel and Turkey to give advice on public
health and community development, the statement said.
(BC-Israel-Turkey) 
</P>
</TEXT>
