<HEADLINE> Iraq, Egypt Sign Deal on Industrial Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Egypt signed a deal
here on Monday on boosting industrial and trade cooperation
between the two Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The deal was inked by Iraqi Industry Minister Adnan
Abdul-Majeed and visiting Egyptian Industry Minister Soleiman
Redha, who arrived here last Friday at the head of a 80-person
delegation representing 40 Egyptian companies, the Iraqi News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries will establish
industrial bases in both countries and Egypt will provide Iraq
with industrial equipment and goods within the framework of the
oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Trade relations between Iraq and Egypt have greatly developed
under the oil-food program though the two Arab countries have not
restored full diplomatic ties cut off following the 1991 Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraqi Trade Ministry, Iraqi imports from
Egypt totaled 550 million U.S. dollars in the first five phases
of the oil-for-food deal, making Egypt the country's number one
trading partner in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food program, Iraq is allowed to export
5.26 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to
buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its 24
million people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has already signed 75 million dollars worth of
contracts with Egyptian companies under the current sixth phase
of the deal which started last May, according to the Iraqi
Trade Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A joint Iraqi-Egyptian committee is to meet next month to
discuss economic and technical cooperation between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
