<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Discuss Test Extension on Belgian Beef Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Belgian exports of beef may
have to be submitted to extended mandatory dioxin tests should
European Union veterinary experts decide to do so this week.
</P>
<P>
EU officials said Monday that a two-day meeting, slated for
Wednesday and Thursday, by the union's standing veterinary
committee would consider whether or not to omit from compulsory
tests Belgian exports of beef.
</P>
<P>
The tests are aimed to detect highly toxic dioxins.
</P>
<P>
Belgium has stated that there is no dioxin risk in beef and has
agreed to put only poultry and pork under the tests.
</P>
<P>
The EU officials said that Belgium may have to continue testing
beef until mid-September. The standing veterinary committee
originally set an end-of-August deadline for testing Belgian beef.
</P>
<P>
Dioxins entered the food chain in Belgium from contaminated
animal feed. Scientific tests are designed to detect high levels
of polychlorinated biphenyls (PCB), chemicals which in turn
indicate dioxin contamination.
</P>
<P>
A PCB level of 200 nanograms per gram of animal fat was set by
the standing veterinary committee as the danger level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
