<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Groups Call for National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Talks between the Fatah movement
of the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) and an opposition
group ended on Monday with both sides calling for national unity
ahead of the final status negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Fatah led by PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat and the Syria-based
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine (DFLP) headed by
Nayef Hawatmeh also agreed to speed up preparations to declare a
Palestinian state in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip with Arab
East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
"The dangers and the challenges of the final status
negotiations (with Israel) demand coherence and the putting aside
of the disagreements over the Oslo agreement," the two sides said in
a joint communique.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting between Arafat and Hawatmeh was their first
since 1993 when the PLO signed the Oslo accord with the Israeli
government. The DFLP and seven other Syria-based groups reject the
accord.
</P>
<P>
The talks were aimed at ending rivalry within Palestinian
groups and unifying Palestinian ranks before the start of
negotiations with Israel on the final status of a Palestinian
entity, East Jerusalem and the Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The two groups called for a national dialog among all
Palestinian groups.
</P>
<P>
"Our success in holding a comprehensive dialog will mark an
outstanding achievement," Hawatmeh said after his talks with
Arafat on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the formation of a coalition of all Palestinian
factions to direct the negotiations with Israel. Arafat is
currently directing such talks.
</P>
<P>
The final communique said the PLO's Executive Committee would
supervise the negotiations with Israel since it is the sole
representative of the Palestinian people. The DFLP is represented
on the committee.
</P>
<P>
The DFLP secretary general said his group and Fatah have agreed
to hold more talks in the near future and that he hoped other
factions would join in.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Fatah delegation, Salim Zaanoun, head of the
Palestinian National Council, told reporters that "we are in a
period in which the Palestinian National Authority should not be
left alone to face the final status questions."
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who left Cairo later in the day for Saudi Arabia, held
talks earlier this month with another rejectionist group, the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine. In their final
statement, they agreed to end their rivalry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
