<HEADLINE> Russia Continues Assault on Militants in Daghestan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian troops continued their
strikes on Islamic militants in its Daghestan republic Monday as
President Boris Yeltsin described the operation as the "number one
priority."
</P>
<P>
The Russian military said Monday that federal troops had killed
140 Islamic gunmen in bombing raids on rebel strongholds Sunday, a
figure which it said brought total rebel deaths to more than 600
since the start of fighting two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Russian warplanes carried out 36 bombing raids on rebel
positions Sunday alone.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was shown on television meeting Daghestan's regional
leader, Magomedali Magomedov. Pounding his fingers on a table,
Yeltsin said, "Daghestan is now our number one priority. Be aware
of that."
</P>
<P>
The new Russian prime minister, Vladimir Putin, vowed on August
10 to put down the revolt in two weeks. The deadline expires on
Tuesday and so far the situation in Daghestan, which borders the
breakaway Chechen republic, has been tense.
</P>
<P>
Russian military officials say they want to cripple the rebels
with artillery and air power before trying to storm their
positions in order to minimize their troops casualties.
</P>
<P>
"At the present moment they are blockaded, held in a
semi-circle. They cannot escape, and our intention is to destroy
them completely," Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo told RTR
state television Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, the rebels, led by Chechen warlord Shamil Basayev,
said they had quit a district of Daghestan where they had been
holding several villages in the two-week standoff with federal
troops.
</P>
<P>
But a Russian Defense Ministry spokesman was quoted as saying
in the Daghestani regional capital Makhachkala that the reported
withdrawal of rebels was "blatant, unprincipled, unpardonable
lies aimed at confusing and misinforming the mass media."
</P>
<P>
He said federal troops still had about 100 rebel fighters
surrounded in Tando, a tiny but strategically important hamlet
that has been the scene of fierce fighting over the past week.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials say federal troops have cut off all escape
routes for the rebels in Tando. 
</P>
</TEXT>
