<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work-Related Illness to Rise: Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The amount of work-related
illness is likely to soar over the next 10 years, according to
research conducted in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The study, commissioned by Norwich Union Healthcare in Britain,
found that far from improving the working environment, the march
of new technology could lead to an epidemic of sickness-related
industrial claims.
</P>
<P>
Nearly three-quarters of GPs (General Practitioner) surveyed in
Britain predicted that the number of patients suffering from
work-related illness would rise over the coming decade, according
to a BBC report on the research, which was based on responses from
100 GPs and 100 personnel directors.
</P>
<P>
Personnel directors took an equally gloomy view. Nearly half
admitted that technological advances in the workplace were
creating new complaints, while 68 percent said companies needed to
re-think their approach to occupational health.
</P>
<P>
Among the complaints which are set to become commonplace are
repetitive strain injury (RSI), bad backs and eye strain.
</P>
<P>
Sue Summers, Norwich Union Healthcare spokesperson, was quoted
by BBC as saying, "Managers will face all sorts of challenges in
the new millennium, not least the possibility of increased staff
absence resulting from today's office environment."
</P>
<P>
"Our research shows that companies need to start thinking about
re-evaluating the way in which they look after the health of their
employees, in order to ensure their workplace is a safe and
healthy environment," Sue Summers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
