<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Get Extra 3 Billion Dollars in Oil Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Iran is expected to gain more
than 3 billion U.S. dollars in additional oil revenue this year
as a result of the current oil price recovery, according to the
official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA).
</P>
<P>
Quoting a projection made by a global energy studies center,
IRNA said Iran's windfall is the second highest among members of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Iran is the second largest producer in OPEC, with a daily yield
of about 3.6 million barrels. The number one producer, Saudi
Arabia, is likely to gain an extra oil revenue of 8 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The center warned that oil price rises also bring undesirables
too, namely higher global inflation, more non-OPEC output and
lower demand growth.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices skyrocketed from about 12 dollars a barrel at the
beginning of this year to over 19 dollars a barrel at present,
because of output cuts by 11 members of OPEC.
</P>
<P>
The center warned against further oil price hiking, which
it said would harm producers and consumers alike.
</P>
<P>
It urged OPEC to stem the price rises by taking the
opportunity at next month's ministerial meeting to clarify plans
to boost production according to market condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
