<HEADLINE> Israel to Increase Aid to Quake-Hit Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel on Monday decided to
provide more medical equipment for Turkey and help re-construct
its communications network severely damaged in a devastating
earthquake last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a statement that it has decided to
dispatch two cargo planes to transport medicine and medical
equipment to Turkey in response to a request from the Turkish Red
Crescent.
</P>
<P>
Other measures included providing assistance in restoring
Turkey's battered communications network and organizing special
seminars both in Israel and Turkey to give advice on public
health and community development, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Besides emergency supplies, Israel has sent more than 380
rescue workers and doctors to Turkey, a close ally of Israel in
the region, to help in the search and care for the survivors.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli rescue team, still staying in Turkey after most
foreign rescue teams have left, Monday pulled a three-year-old boy
alive from the ruins of collapsed buildings in the city of
Cinarcik, 50 kilometers south of Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-medical team, which has set up the largest field
hospital equipped with an intensive-care unit and a 100-bed ward,
will stay in Turkey for about a month, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
A committee headed by director-generals of the Prime
Minister's Office and the Defense Ministry visited Turkey Monday
to discuss what additional assistance Turkey would need, the
radio said. 
</P>
