<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Works Out Anti-Malaria Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Health Ministry
has prepared anti-malaria guidelines in a bid to prevent and
control the epidemic in the country, a senior official said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Alemayehu Seifu, chief of Epidemiology and AIDS Control
Department of the ministry, said at a press conference here that
the guidelines are designed to help health workers across the
country to carry out malaria diagnosis and treatment in a
standardized manner.
</P>
<P>
Malaria is one of the major killer diseases in Ethiopia. Each
year, close to three to five million people in the country are
affected by malaria, which is among the leading causes of
hospitalization and hospital death in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is officially estimated that about two thirds of the
country's population are at risk of malaria infection.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government has been for years making efforts to
curb the spread of malaria.
</P>
<P>
The National Malaria Social Mobilization Week is due to be
observed from 24-30 August this year.
</P>
<P>
The annual nationwide campaign is held with a view to further
bolster the participation of governmental and non-governmental
organizations as well as the public at large in the fight against
the disease.
</P>
<P>
August is a month suitable for malaria breeding in most parts
of Ethiopia, according to medical experts.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that anti-malaria chemicals have been sprayed
in many parts of the country to preempt possible outbreak of the
epidemic following the rainy season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
