<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Chief Sounds Alarm on Angolan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food
Program (WFP) Monday said that the civil war in Angola has created
levels of misery and despair among the people that are virtually
unmatched anywhere else in the world.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Catherine Bertini, the WFP's executive
director, was briefing the Security Council on the humanitarian
situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Bertini said that Angolans have become so desperate to
survive they are even risking death to collect landmine marker
sticks that are then used as cooking fuel.
</P>
<P>
Bertini signaled that the lack of food in Angola is one of the
most serious problems facing the people. She said that farmers
abandoned their fields after the latest outbreak of fighting in
December 1998, so food supplies in the commercial markets are
shrinking even as prices spiral beyond reach.
</P>
<P>
Malnutrition levels are becoming extremely alarming, she said,
citing the town of Malange in southern Angola where several people
are dying every day from lack of food. Hundreds of internally
displaced people (IDPs) have fled to Malange because of fighting
in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
The WFP currently has an emergency operation of 38 million U.S.
dollars in Angola to give food to 800,000 vulnerable people and
IDPs. The operation, which began after a ceasefire collapsed late
last year and fighting resumed, originally targeted 500,000 people
and will expand to 1.2 million next year.
</P>
<P>
However, the food aid agency has received 40 percent of the
funding it needs for the new emergency, and Bertini strongly
urged donors to give to Angolan relief.
</P>
<P>
Bertini also underlined the security issues that hamper the
work of humanitarian agencies working in Angola. Since 1993, the
WFP has lost six staff members in Angola to armed attacks. In the
last eight months, two U.N.-chartered aircraft have been shot
down, with a loss of 23 lives including one WFP employee.
</P>
<P>
"Peace is the only answer to save the lives of millions of
Angolans," she said. Up until the renewal of the civil war, the
WFP had been conducting rehabilitation activities in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The country's progress in rebuilding has been severely
undermined by the renewed fighting, she said, calling for
serious efforts by governments worldwide to bring peace to the
southwestern African nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
