<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni government has launched a campaign against
poverty since 1995 as part of its economic reforms, but the result
are not satisfactory, according to a report issued by Yemeni
scholars.
</P>
<P>
The report said the government has set up funds for social
welfare and development and raised salary for state employees, but
the measures are facing numerous difficulties in practice, the
Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics in the report revealed that the number of poor
people has increased from 3ive program for the eradication of
poverty. The report said the high poverty rate is due to low
economic growth, low income, high cost of living and the
abandoning of state subsidies for basic food.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria and Jordan plan to establish a common market
together with Lebanon, official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The plan was raised in talks Sunday between Syrian Minister of
Economy and Trade Mohammad al-Imadi and a top-level Jordanian
trade delegation, the Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Syrian exports to Jordan have declined from 140 million dollars
in 1996 to 40 million last year while Jordanian exports to Syria
fell from 57 million dollars to 21 million over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The two sides stressed that improvement of trade would only be
achieved through direct import and export deals among businessmen
and exporters of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Basic Syrian imports from Jordan include flour, lime, chemical
and organic by-products, medicine and paper. Major Syrian exports
to Jordan include petroleum, cotton, petroleum by-products,
natural gas, textiles, clothes, mineral water and soft drinks, and
onions.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister Youssef Wali has said
that Egypt bases its agricultural policy on challenges,
economic liberation and legislature, and the establishment of
dynamic relations with international research institutions.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has attached great importance to cooperation with the
consultative group of international research centers of the World
Bank, said Wali, who is also minister of Agriculture and Land
Reclamation.
</P>
<P>
Wali made the remarks at the opening session of the sixth
international conference on the development of barren lands and
the challenges in next century, the Arabic daily Al Ahram reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Wali added that Egypt has embarked on reserving plantations and
developing organic technology. Two relation research centers, the
biggest in Africa, have been established.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a fishery and a veterinary institutions, and research
centers on desert have also been set up.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Visa International has achieved issuance of over
3 million credit cards in the Gulf region since June, 1996,
according to the company's statistics for the quarter which ended
June, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Usage of Visa cards in the Gulf rose by over 600 percent in
the past three years, said the statistics quoted by Gulf News on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Oman has toped Visa International's list as the fastest
growing market in the world, with 90,000 Omanis now owning
Visa cards.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The gas fields in Egypt's Western Desert are producing
23.24 million cubic meters of natural gas, or 32 percent of the
country's total production, per day, Oil Minister Hamdi el-Banbi
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
El-Banbi said on a visit to the Obayad field that 89 gas fields
were discovered in the last six years, increasing Egypt's proven
gas reserves to 1.14 trillion cubic meters, the country's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Seven discoveries were made during the last six months with a
daily output of 6.3 million cubic meters, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the success in the oil and gas sector to the
incentives offered to foreign investments.


