<HEADLINE> WTO Applicants Be Allowed to Negotiate First: Supachai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Countries applying for WTO
membership should be allowed to participate its trade negotiations
before their formal accession so that they can prepare themselves
more fully and actively once they are accepted, WTO
Director-General-elect Supachai Panitchpakdi said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It need not be stressed that the increase in the number of
active participants can greatly extend the scope of global
liberalization and thus strengthen multilateral trade system,"
Supachai, Thai deputy prime minister and commerce minister, said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at the start of the three-day Meeting of
Senior Officials on the Future of World Trade Organization (WTO)
Trade Agenda and Developing Countries held here from Monday to
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said developing economies should collectively search for
ways to strengthen their participation in multilateral trade
negotiations and integrate themselves into the global trading
system, which would lead to a significant expansion in
international trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
He called for greater attempts on the part of developed
countries to lower barriers to agricultural trade through an
across-the-board tariff reduction, including the lowering of
out-quota tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also discuss the impact of the Asian economic
crisis on trade and liberalization process, the ways to enhance
the participation of least-developed countries, scope of future
trade agenda and other issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
