<HEADLINE> Falling Pay Eases Rate Fears In Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Pay awards across industry in
Britain are still falling, with salary rises posing little threat
of pushing up inflation.
</P>
<P>
The average pay settlement in manufacturing during the three
months to the end of June was 2.7 percent, down from 2.8 percent
in the previous quarter and from 3.5 percent in the same period
last year, according to a survey by the Confederation of British
Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
The news of falling pay comes despite an acceleration in
economic growth, a 19-year low in unemployment and official
figures which say pay is rising.
</P>
<P>
The CBI's Pay Data Bank survey also showed more companies are
setting pay rises at or below the government's 2.5 percent
inflation target.
</P>
<P>
It's chief economic adviser Kate Barker said the figures showed
there was no need for the Bank of England to raise interest rates
in the near future to fend off inflation.
</P>
<P>
Last moth, members of the Bank of England's Monetary Policy
Committee, which sets interest rates, were sharply divided on the
question of whether inflation would start to rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
