<HEADLINE> France Telecom to Launch New Internet Phone Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- France Telecom, France's state
monopoly of telecommunications, will launch in 2000 a new
technology for putting together portable phones and internet.
</P>
<P>
The executive officer of France Telecom, Michel Bon, said that
the technology, called General Package Radio Service (GPRS), will
help push forward the marketing of portable phones for connecting
with internet.
</P>
<P>
GPRS has been undergoing experiments with two phone producers,
the French company Alcatel and U.S. Motorola, with great success,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The connection of portable phones with private computers is
developing with great steps and is making the industrial
perspective of webphone more uncertain," he said.
</P>
<P>
GPRS will help stimulate the use of portable private computers
connected with portable phones as a space of webphone, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal on Seaport, Safe Passage Reached Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators Monday reached a deal on the construction of a seaport
in Gaza and the opening of a safe passage between Gaza and the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The two issues are aspects of the Palestinian-Israeli Wye
Accord signed last October in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat told Israel Radio
that the two sides will accelerate talks to iron out difference on
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank, the major part of the
accord.
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, the seaport will begin construction on
October 1, when the southern route of the safe passage, between
Gaza and Hebron, is also due to open. The northern route of the
passage,which links Gaza and Ramallah, will open in January,
Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
In the deal, the Palestinians have reiterated their security
commitments, including the continued collection of illegal
weapons, and the scale-down of Palestinian police, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the seaport and the safe passage, long delayed
by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's hard-line predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu, will undoubtedly help restore the
confidence-building between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Erekat, however, admitted that the two sides are still locked
in a dispute over the timetable of Israeli troop redeployments
in the West Bank and the release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye Accord, Israel has to hand over another 13
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians in three stages that
should have finished by the end of January. But Netanyahu froze
the agreement in early December after carrying out the first stage.
</P>
<P>
Ousting Netanyahu on a platform to revive the peace process in
the Israeli elections in May, Barak has promised to carry out the
remaining two stages, but he has proposed some changes to the
timetable.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have reluctantly accepted his proposal to
carry out the second troop withdrawal in October.
</P>
<P>
But they have rejected Barak's suggestion that the final stage
of redeployment be postponed until early 2000, when the final
status talks dealing with thorny issues like Jerusalem and
settlements are supposed to have been well under way.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Palestinian
National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat said Sunday that the
Palestinians were insisting the implementation of the Wye
agreement be completed by November 30.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Palestinian prisoners, the two sides had
reached an agreement on the timeline, under which the first batch
of prisoners will be released on September 1 and the second on
October 8. But dispute remains over the number and terms of the
prisoners to be released.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians demand that Israel release another 650 Palestinian
political prisoners jailed for anti-Israel activities .
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel reached a verbal agreement within
the framework of the Wye Accord, under which Israel should release
750 Palestinian political prisoners jailed in Israel. But the
Palestinians accused Netanyahu of cheating by including 150 common
criminals in the first group of 250 freed prisoners last year.
</P>
<P>
The government of Barak, however, insists that the Wye accord
did not specify what kind of prisoners should be released and it
would continue to include common criminals in the remaining 500
prisoners to be released.
</P>
<P>
In the several rounds of talks over the last few weeks, Erekat
and Israeli chief negotiator Barak's envoy Gilad Sher have failed
to resolve their differences on the redeployment and prisoner
issues. Israeli officials said that Barak might hold a summit with
Arafat to iron out the dispute.
</P>
<P>
But Erekat told Israel Radio that he did not expect such a
summit would take place before the disputes were resolved.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides will continue talks to solve the
problems, adding the Palestinian side would "exert every effort
possible" to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
He denied charges by Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy Monday
that his planned trip with Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas to
Washington this week was intended to aim at enlisting U.S. pressure on
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said they were invited by Washington to arrange details
on Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's coming visit to the
region, including the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
Denying that he is seeking help from Washington when the
Israeli-Palestinian talks enter a critical stage, Erekat said he
has postponed his trip, originally planned about 10 days ago,
because of the talks. He will meet Albright Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Albright will start her trip on September 1 with an aim of
ensuring the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks are on the track and
trying to restart the stalled talks between Israel and Syria.
</P>
</TEXT>
