<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Robust Asia-Pacific Internet Growth Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of Asia-Pacific
Internet users is expected to surpass 374 million by year-end
2005, up from just over 39 million by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to a forecast report released Monday by U.S.
information technology research firm Yankee Group, the number of
paying subscribers, which hovered just under 19 million in the
region at year-end 1998, will grow to over 175 million by the end
of 2005.
</P>
<P>
The Yankee Group notes the difference between a paying Internet
access subscriber and the number of users (the addressable
business-to-consumer audience), as there are often multiple users
for one subscription account.
</P>
<P>
The forecast shows China becoming the leading Asia-Pacific
nation in terms of Internet users in 2001, with about 40 million
people online. By 2005, the report said, China should surpass the
United States to have the most users in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The implication of this Asia-Pacific subscriber and user
growth will be enormous on global e-commerce opportunities, from
business-to-business sourcing, to business-to-consumer marketing,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Factors that have constrained the historical growth of the
Internet in Asia include the regulatory, commercial and access
issues that have begun to change and will drive Internet growth
and penetration going forward, according to the research firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
