<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS States Owe Russia 2.4 Billion Dollars in Energy Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The combined debts of other
member states of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) for
fuel and energy supplied by Russia reached 59.6 billion rubles
(about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars) in the first six months of the
year, the Russian Energy Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the debts, 40.4 billion rubles (1.63 billion
dollars), are for gas supplied by the Gazprom monopoly. Gazprom's
CIS clients made no more than 3.2 percent of their payments for
gas in cash.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that Ukraine is the biggest debtor, owing
287.8 billion rubles (11.6 billion dollars). Moldova is the second
with a debt of 11.6 billion rubles (467.7 million dollars),
followed by Kazakhstan, 11.4 billion rubles (460 million dollars)
and Belarus, 7.4 billion rubles (298 million dollars), the
Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
