<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-23 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Iraqis Killed in U.S.-British Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Two Iraqi civilians were killed
and a third one injured on Monday in U.S. and British warplanes'
attacks on civilian targets in northern Iraq, an Iraqi military
spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:35 (0635 GMT), nine formations
of U.S. and British warplanes coming from Turkish airspace
violated northern Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Erbil and Neineva
provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy planes bombed some civilian facilities in Bashiqa
town in Neineva province, some 450 kilometers north of Baghdad,
killing two civilians and injuring another one, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back at the
enemy planes and repulsed them to their Turkish base.
</P>
<P>
Enemy warplanes coming from Saudi bases also violated
southern Iraqi airspace in the day, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The latest U.S.-British bombardment of Iraqi targets came five
days after the Pentagon announced the U.S.-British air
raids against Iraqi targets in the no-fly zones will be suspended
if Iraqi air defenses stop targetting allied warplanes.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after U.S. and British warplanes
bombed some residential areas and targets outside of the no-fly
zones last week and killed 20 Iraqi civilians and injured 10
others.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led
western allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed
aim of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite
Muslims in the south against attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S.-British airstrikes against Iraqi
targets, Iraq began to fire at U.S. and British warplanes
patrolling the no-fly zones.
</P>
</TEXT>
