<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Afghanistan to Discuss Transit Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Afghanistan will
hold talks over the controversy on Afghan Transit Trade Agreement
(ATTA) on Tuesday, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's top official responsible for foreign affairs Mulla
Mohammad Hassan Akhund is arriving in Islamabad as the head of a
high level Afghan delegation including senior commercial
officials.
</P>
<P>
Hassan will hold official talks with his Pakistani counterpart
Sartaj Aziz to discuss bilateral issues, especially the transit
trade agreement, officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to Pakistan official statistics, the market of
smuggled goods in Pakistan is depriving the national exchequer of
over 5.5 billion rupees each year mainly due to exemptions
provided to Afghanistan under the ATTA.
</P>
<P>
The ATTA was signed in 1960s to facilitate the foreign trade of
Afghanistan who has no port. Under the agreement, Afghanistan only
pays a meager amount of service charges for the transit trade
through Pakistan and enjoys exemptions of duties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
