<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Trains High-Level Mass Media Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Some 105 people from
Ethiopian mass media began receiving a short training course on
planning, management, and journalism on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Information and Culture
Vice-Minister Bisrat Tena-Gashaw said that the existence of
well-equipped mass media is essential for the democratization
process.
</P>
<P>
She said special attention has been given to training and human
resource development in the sector over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
The 11-day training course, attended by senior media
executives, general managers and journalists, is organized by the
Ethiopian Mass Media Training Institute in collaboration with the
United States-based Duke University.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian mass media has developed remarkably in recent years.
In addition to the state-owned news agency, radio and television
station, the country has about 140 kinds of newspapers and
magazines.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 foreign information institutions have deployed
reporters in the Horn of Africa country. 
</P>
