<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday met in a closed-door session to be briefed by senior U.N.
officials on the current situation in Angola, which has been
plunged into a civil war for decades.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation Security Council will be briefed by Hedi Annabi,
U.N. assistant secretary-general for peacekeeping operations,
Sergio Vieira de Mello, undersecretary-general for humanitarian
affairs, Catherine Bertini, director of the World Food Program,
and Carol Bellamy, executive director of the United Nations
Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
The briefing came at a time when the United Nations is planning
to open a liaison office in Angola to explore ways to restore
peace in the country, six months after the withdrawal of U.N.
peacekeepers from the southwestern African country.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has agreed to allow the new U.N. office,
which will set up links with security and civilian authorities.
</P>
<P>
U.N. humanitarian operations have continued to be conducted in
the African country since the departure of the peacekeeping
forces.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations spent 10 years and millions of U.S. dollars
trying to bring peace to the African nation, where civil war broke
out soon after its 1975 independence from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
At present, fighting, population displacement, drought and
disease have wrought "exceptional food emergencies" in 16 African
countries with Angola hit hardest, the United Nations Food and
Agricultural Organization said in early August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
