<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First British Beef Heads For Europe Since 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The first British beef to be
exported since the lifting of the worldwide ban on the product in
March 1996 is on its way to Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, UK Agriculture Minister Nick Brown told the BBC Monday
that it will take a long time for British beef to reclaim its
share of the market.
</P>
<P>
A symbolic 45 kilograms of fillet steak left St Merryns in
Cornwall on the same day, on route to the continent via Dover. The
tiny amount shows how hard it will be for British farmers to
regain lost markets.
</P>
<P>
The consignment of beef has been ordered by a Brussels hotel
for a British Meat and Livestock Commmission's celebration lunch.
</P>
<P>
Brown said that it is a start on beef exports from the United
Kingdom. "We have been out of exports since 1996. The shutters
came down at probably the worst possible time because exports were
at a record high," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Brown admitted that it will be a very long haul to get beef
export to anything like they were in normal trading conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
