<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement on Trade in Ozone Depleting Substances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- An agreement on licensing the
imports and exports of ozone-depleting substances is expected to
enter into force, the U.N. Environment Program (UNEP) said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
By August 12, twenty countries and regions had approved the
Montreal Amendment to the Montreal Protocol on Substances that
Deplete the Ozone Layer, which met the precondition of at least 20
ratifications for the pact to be effective in November 10 this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Amendment stipulates that 90 days after the realization of
20 ratifications it will enter into force automatically.
</P>
<P>
The document provides for signatories to establish and
implement a system for licensing trade in ozone-depleting
substances (ODS) by January 1, 2000 and report to the secretariat
on the establishment of such a system.
</P>
<P>
"The entry into force of this Amendment is a timely measure
which should assist the international community to monitor trade
in ozone depleting substances and curb potential illegal trade,"
said UNEP Executive Director Klaus Toepfer in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The primary aim of the Montreal Protocol on Substances that
Deplete the Ozone Layer and its Amendments is to phase out both
production and consumption of ODS in order to protect human health
and the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Police Take Responsibility for Law and Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Interim
Administrative Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) Monday announced that
UNMIK police had started taking over primary responsibility for
law and order in Pristina, capital of the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the U.N. spokesman, told a press
conference here that the police assumed investigative authority
and jurisdiction for enforcing criminal codes, conducting
investigations, making arrests for criminal offense and
interfacing with the community.
</P>
<P>
The UNMIK police will continue to be supported by international
peacekeeping forces in Kosovo, which were sent into the Serbian
province under a U.N. resolution. The two units will continue their
joint work in all communities in an effort to reduce violence and
crime.
</P>
<P>
The security situation is reportedly worsening as a lot of
non-Albanians were persecuted in Kosovo by the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army, whose fighters returned to the Serbian province
after Yugoslavia honored an agreement with NATO by prompt
withdrawal of its troops and security forces out of Kosovo in
June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
