<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Review of Contract Holds in Iraq Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday asked for an all-out review of the contracts
holds in the oil-for-food program as they pose "serious
implications" for the humanitarian program in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council on the implementation of
the new 180 day phase of the oil-for-food program beginning May
25, Annan expressed concern about the number of contracts
currently on hold, worth some 500 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He urged Iraq and the U.N. sanctions committee to give priority
to contracts which have a direct impact on the well-being of
children, particularly on nutrition, water and sanitation
supplies.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that at current prices and volumes Iraq will
have the capacity to export 6.3 billion dollars worth of oil in
the phase or Phase VI ending November 21, surpassing the 5.2
billion dollars authorized by the Security Council last year.
</P>
<P>
However, there was a shortfall of 3.1 billion dollars in the
total revenues authorized for the humanitarian program under
phases IV and V due to the substantial fall in oil prices, the
report noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
