<HEADLINE> Namibia to Award Freedom Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Namibia's ruling party is
pushing a controversial bill to subsidize war veterans through
parliament, it is reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The War Veterans Subvention Bill, debated in the upper house of
 parliament, the National Council, won overwhelming support of
parliamentarians of the ruling South West African People's
Organization (Swapo) on Monday, according to South African Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
The bill is aimed at creating a war veteran subvention trust
fund which will benefit former Swapo freedom fighters who are
currently aged 55 and above or the beneficiaries -- orphans and
relatives of those who laid down their lives in the liberation
struggle.
</P>
<P>
During the debate, Swapo's whip in parliament, Henock ya
Kasita, who sponsored the bill, described it as "a step in the
right direction".
</P>
<P>
"It is time for the liberation forces to be remembered for a
job well done."
</P>
<P>
He said: "They (members of the liberation forces) laid down
their precious lives for freedom and independence of this country.
Today, Namibia occupies its rightful place among countries of the
world, a reality that cannot be doubted."
</P>
<P>
He proposed that the amount of money to be given to the
beneficiaries be disbursed by a parliamentary joint committee
comprised of both houses, and that such payments ought to be done
monthly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
