<HEADLINE> U.N. Panel to Study Environmental Impact of NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
organizing scientists from eight countries to study the impact of
NATO bombing on Danube river, the second longest river in Europe,
a U.N. spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the U.N. spokesman, told a press
conference here that the Balkans Task Force, jointly organized by
the U.N. Environment Program (UNEP) and the U.N. Center for Human
Settlement (Habitat) will visit the Yugoslav section of Danube
river to assess the environmental impact of the recent conflict.
</P>
<P>
The scientists are nine industrial experts from the Czech
Republic, Hungry, France, Germany, Romania, Russia, Slovakia and
Sweden, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
They will visit potential pollution "hot-spot" up and
down-stream of the Novi-Sad oil refinery, Pancevo industrial
complex and a tributary near the Zastava car factory in
Kraguejevac, the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The team will also visit the Iron Gates dam on the border
between Yugoslavia and Romania where the Djerdap reservoir holds
extensive layers of sediment that can absorb organic matter, and
toxic and hazardous waste possibly carried down the river Danube.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to assess the environmental health of the Danube
before and after the conflict, the scientists will collect
sediment and water samples.
</P>
<P>
They will also measure the accumulation of pollutants like
polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) in living mussels, in order to
get a picture of the possible toxic releases to the Danube in the
hours immediately after the damage to industrial facilities in
Yugoslavia, caused by the 79-day air strikes by the U.S.-led NATO.
</P>
<P>
After the mission, which will end Saturday, the samples will be
sent to independent laboratory for detailed analysis.
</P>
<P>
This is the third team since July to be sent into Yugoslavia to
assess the environmental damage caused by NATO air strikes on
selected industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
On July 18-27, a team of international experts visited
Yugoslavia to assess the environmental damage caused by the
conflict at selected industrial complexes. A second team, based in
the provincial capital of Pristina, is currently working in close
cooperation with the U.N. Mission in Kosovo, known as UNMIK.
</P>
<P>
A fourth team will begin work next month on an assessment of
impacts on the region's biological diversity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Science and Technology Development in China, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 23 (Xinhua) -- What strikes him the most is
the great change in the 50 years of new China, Nobel Physics Prize
laureate Chen Ning Yang told Xinhua correspondents in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
Professor Yang, former Director of the Theoretical Physics
Department at State University of New York at Stony Brook, spoke
highly of China's progress in the field of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
China's history of science and technology was a blank paper in
the 1920s, he said. Soon after the founding of the People's
Republic of China in 1949, science and technology has begun to
develop in a remarkably fast way, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Yang pointed to the successful test of nuclear and hydrogen
bombs and the development of rocket and satellite technologies in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
"Such accomplishments require the efforts of tens of thousands
of scientists and skilled workers," he said, adding that it is
unprecedented to see so many qualified personnel to be trained in
a short period of 15 years.
</P>
<P>
"Such an achievement is unseen even in the history of world
science and technology," said Yang, who shared the Nobel Prize in
1957 with Tsung-Dao Lee, another Chinese American for their
penetrating investigation of the so-called parity laws which has
led to important discoveries regarding the elementary particles.
</P>
<P>
In the years of reform and openness in China, new developments
have taken place, particularly in the substantial increase of the
number of people receiving higher-learning education which laid
foundation for further scientific and technological progress,
Professor Yang said.
</P>
<P>
He paid great attention to the growing funds that the Chinese
Government has been allocating for the science and technology
education and research in an effort to meet the needs of the
country's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The 77-year-old well-known scientist spoke favorably of the
Chinese Communist Party for its "great contributions" to China's
reunification, construction and its international status.
</P>
<P>
Yang was born in 1922 when warlords tangled in fighting all
over the country and left China to the United States for further
study in 1945 during the Japanese occupation of China. He recalled
what he saw in the early years of his life.
</P>
<P>
There was no electric light in his native city of Hefei, the
capital of Anhui Province and the streets there were so narrow
that they could not allow buses to go in.
</P>
<P>
The situation in many other parts of China was even worse as
there were cases of warlords killing and prevailing poverty, he
said.
</P>
<P>
When he first came back to China in 1971, Yang was deeply
impressed by what happened in the 26 years of his stay overseas.
China's mainland, once suffering from the rule of separatist
warlord regimes, became unified.
</P>
<P>
As the biggest developing country, China has won international
recognition of its due status, Yang remarked, joining many
international figures in believing that China will score more
achievements in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Professor Yang retired from his 33-year Department post in May,
but still cares about international and Chinese scientific trends.
He is now helping Qinhua University of China to build a high level
academic center.
</P>
<P>
He is happy to be invited to participate in the celebrations in
Beijing of the 50th anniversary of the PRC, describing the
founding of the PRC as "a big event in the history of China and
one of the few important events in the 20th century". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
