<HEADLINE> British, Irish Governments Deny Split over IRA Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The British and Irish Governments
have insisted they are at one on the peace process in Northern
Ireland, despite disagreeing in public over the IRA (Irish
Republican Army) ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Irish Foreign Minister David Andrews told reporters on Monday
that "in the round," he and Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary
of State, Mo Mowlam, had agreed the ceasefire was intact.
</P>
<P>
But Mowlam immediately interrupted him to take issue with that,
saying: "We did reach that conclusion but I am awaiting additional
information from America and the Irish before I make a final
decision."
</P>
<P>
The two ministers were speaking at a news conference on Monday
in Belfast, shortly after a meeting between the two sides at
Stormont, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Andrews described the recent murder of north Belfast man
Charles Bennett as a brutal outrage, but said he felt the
ceasefire was holding.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam is expected to give her assessment sometime this week on
the state of the IRA ceasefire, after consulting her police and
army security advisors. She has denied that there is any
disagreement between the UK and Irish Governments on the subject,
but she said she was not yet in a position to judge the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"I am reviewing the state of the IRA ceasefire and others in
the light of recent events which I continue to view very seriously
indeed," she was quoted as saying. "As I have always said, I will
not rush to judgement, but when I have the relevant information I
will make my decision known."
</P>
<P>
But Andrews was quoted as telling: "I think it's fair to say
the ceasefire has been intact for a number of years now and the
IRA, in the round, have not been using their weapons. That is my
view and it is the view of the (Irish) government."
</P>
<P>
The IRA ceasefire has been under scrutiny since the recent
killing of Bennett, and speculation that republican paramilitaries
were involved in a gun-running plot to post arms from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam is under pressure from unionists to halt paramilitary
prisoner releases, if she judges that the IRA has broken its
ceasefire. Her decision could have a major impact on next month's
review of the implementation of the Good Friday Agreement, which
will be chaired by former U.S. Senator George Mitchell, who
chaired last year's peace talks in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The review, which starts on 6 September, is an attempt to break
the political logjam over the formation of Northern Ireland's
executive and weapons decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC Radio Ulster Monday, Sinn Fein's chief
negotiator, Martin McGuinness, warned the Northern Ireland
secretary against halting the early prison releases if the IRA is
found to have broken its ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble has said his
party was right to boycott attempts to form a devolved government.
He echoed others in his party who have called on the Northern
Ireland secretary to impose sanctions on Sinn Fein if the IRA is
proved to have been behind the incidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Million Angolans Needing Aid, Senior U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- "In Angola, two million
people are living a precarious existence and are in need of or
dependent on aid," a senior U.N. official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N. undersecretary-general for
humanitarian affairs and emergency relief co-ordinator, told
reporters that "We estimate that another three million people are
entirely inaccessible and their condition is therefore impossible
to assess."
</P>
<P>
He made the statement after he briefed the U.N. Security
Council on the humanitarian situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, 70 percent of the country's population are living
in besieged provincial capitals, or in government-held areas on
the coast," he said. "Intermittent shelling of the provincial
capitals has caused the deaths of many hundreds of civilians and
regularly prevents the delivery of humanitarian assistance."
</P>
<P>
"In the overcrowded provincial capitals, there is a high risk
of outbreak of epidemic diseases due to the lack of sanitation
and safe drinking water and the generally weakened state of the
population," he said.
</P>
<P>
In May a polio epidemic in the vicinity of Benguela and Luanda,
the Angolan capital, resulted in 113 deaths. A meningitis outbreak
was confirmed recently in Kuando Kubango.
</P>
<P>
"Of the two million people known to be in need in Angola,"
600,000 receive humanitarian assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are two main reasons why humanitarian agencies are
unable to do more," he said. "One reason is insecurity and lack of
access and the second reason is funding."
</P>
<P>
Angola has been locked in a civil war shortly after its 1975
independence from Portugal. The Angolan Government and the rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
resumed fighting in December last year, making the humanitarian
situation in the southwestern African country further worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Ruling Coalition Agrees Austerity Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 23 (Xinhua)--At their first session in Berlin, the
two parties governing Germany on Monday reached a consensus over
the bill to cut the country's budget drastically in following
years.
</P>
<P>
After the two-hour meeting in Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
interim residence, top officials from the Social Democratic Party
(SPD) under Schroeder and the Greens party leaded by Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer said they would support the austerity
package in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
" We hope for the support of the parliament, " SPD's
parliamentary fraction chief Peter Struck said after the session.
He said the bill would be passed at this Wednesday's cabinet
session and be sent to the parliament in September for debate and
voting.
</P>
<P>
Struck's counterpart of the Greens party, Kerstin Mueller,
agreed and appealed the labour unions not to ask for too much from
the state.
</P>
<P>
The unions should " take responsibility for all," and it is
false for them to say the bill "socially unjust," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Called "Sparpaket" in German, the package, raised by Finance
Minister Hans Eichel with Schroeder's backing, was aimed to cut
Germany's state budget by 30.4 billion marks in year 2000, 38.6
billion in 2001, 42.2 billion in 2002, and 49.5 billion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
Under the 200-page bill, pension, jobless relief and other
social welfare paying will be strictly limited to grow at the
projected inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
And German tax-payers' burden will be relieved by 46 billion
marks under the three-stage tax reform plan indicated in the bill.
</P>
<P>
While praised by business leaders, the austerity package has
been under continuous fire from Germany's influential unions. They
said Schroeder and his SPD, by raising the pro-business bill in
May, had hurt the interests of the weaks and had betrayed their
boasted line of "social justice". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
