<HEADLINE> Highlight of Diplomatic News Today (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The following is the highlight
of diplomatic news released by Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Leaves Beijing for Bishkek
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin left here today for Bishkek, capital of
Kyrgyzstan, to attend a five-nation summit meeting of China,
Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
 NPC Chairman Meets Dominican President of Senate
</P>
<P>
Even though China and Dominica have not yet established
diplomatic ties, the current visit by President of the Dominican
Senate Ramon Alburquerque will help increase mutual understanding
and friendship, and lay foundation for future cooperation in
various fields, said Li Peng, chairman of the Chinese National
People's Congress Standing Committee, here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Confers with Brunei Sultan
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji today told Hassanal Bolkiah, the Sultan and
head of state of Brunei that he will attend the third informal
meeting between leaders from the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) and leaders from China, Japan and the Republic of
Korea, scheduled to be held in Manila, Philippines, in November.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Meets ROK Defense Minister
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji, in a meeting today with Cho Sung-Tae,
defense minister of the Republic of Korea (ROK), spoke highly of
China-ROK cooperation in all fields since the two countries forged
diplomatic ties seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
Fu Quanyou, chief of the General Staff of Chinese People's
Liberation Army (PLA), today met with Cho Sung-Tae and declared
that the military relations between China and ROK have enjoyed a
steady and healthy development.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Meets Mozambican Defense Minister
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government values its ties with Mozambique and the
Chinese are willing to elevate bilateral friendship and
cooperation to a new level, according to Premier Zhu Rongji, in a
meeting with Mozambican Defense Minister Aguiar Real Mazula today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Meets Mauritian Official
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji said here today that the Chinese government
and its people cherish the traditional Sino-Mauritian friendship
and would like to push forward the existing bilateral friendly
ties.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a meeting with Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Foreign Affairs and International Trade Rajkeswur
Purryag of Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
 Sino-Russian Friendship Hailed
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji today expressed his satisfaction with the
vigorous development of Sino-Russian ties during his meeting with
visiting Russian Vice Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov.
</P>
