<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission Satisfied With Decolonization of New Caledonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The delegation, led by the Fiji Vice Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Tupeni Baba, consisted of Papua New Guinea ambassador to
the U.N. Donigi, Chilean ambassador Juan Eguiguren and Vanuatu
ambassador Salwyn Arutangay.
</P>
<P>
They visited local institutions set up since 1998 to replace
French colonial ones, said the AFP.
</P>
<P>
Besides meeting with local French officials, the U.N. delegates
also met with the leader of the pro-independence Front of
Socialist Kanak National Liberation (FLNKS), Rock Wamytan, and the
pro-French Rally for Caledonia in the Republic (PRCR), Jacques
Lafleur.
</P>
<P>
The FLNKS and PRCR differ over the make-up of the transitional
government, whose chairman is Thiery Lataste, the French high
commissioner in New Caledonia, and its vice-chairman is from the
PRCR.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the U.N. delegation encouraged the local
parties to eliminate their differences and completely implement
the agreement on decolonization signed between the French
government and the local parties in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 agreement is aimed at decolonizing the institutions
before holding a referendum in 15 to 20 years to decide between
independence and a high-degree autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the population are Kanak people opposed to the
French colonial rule of the nickel-rich archipelago since the mid-
19th century.
</P>
<P>
When French Socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin visited New
Caledonia in 1998, he denounced the history of French colonial
rule there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
