<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Go from Weakness to Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Tibetans, who make up 96 percent
of the population of the Tibet Autonomous Region, have seen
themselves grown from a weak group living under a feudal system to
a vigorous one under the leadership of the Communist Party, over
the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetans know the significance of the democratic reforms
that began in the region in 1959 that turned them into masters of
their own destiny. The democratic reforms put an end to the
political and religious dictatorial rule that had long plagued
Tibet and gave the serfs freedom.
</P>
<P>
Raidi, the 61-year-old chairman of the regional People's
Congress Standing Committee, describes his own experience before
1959 as nightmarish. He was born into a poor herdsman's family in
northern Tibet and worked as a servant to herd owners, tribal
chiefs, and living Buddhas from the age of six.
</P>
<P>
He later fled from his oppressive masters and made a living by
begging. "The scars over my body are reminders of the miserable
past," he says.
</P>
<P>
The Thirteen-article Code and Sixteen-article Code were used in
old Tibet to separate people into three classes, each with three
ranks, enforcing the inequality. But the former Tibetan serfs are
their own masters now and their offspring are playing an important
role in economic development.
</P>
<P>
At present, the autonomous region has about 50,000 Tibetan or
other ethnic cadres, accounted for 75 percent of the total number
of cadres.
</P>
<P>
Before the peaceful liberation of Tibet in 1951, only a small
number of monk officials and children of the nobility had the
privilege of studying, and less than two percent of the school-age
children went to school. The illiteracy rate ran as high as 97
percent.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, there were 81.3 percent of the school-age
Tibetan children in school and an education system that went from
preschool to college and university. Since the mid-1980s, to make
it easier for middle school students from Tibet to study in other
parts of China, the Central Government set aside special funds for
Tibetan junior middle-school classes in 16 provinces and
municipalities, involving 13,000 students.
</P>
<P>
Transportation, board and lodging, clothing, and medical care
for those students are all covered by the government.
</P>
<P>
Many Tibetans are living better lives as well with the rapid
development especially since China started its reform and open-up
drive 20 years ago. Under the feudal system, most Tibetan farmers
and herdsmen owned no material goods, but now per household assets
are worth 9,000 yuan in Tibet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
