<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and his German
counterpart Joschka Fischer began a 24-hour visit to Kosovo
Tuesday morning to urge all groups in Kosovo to abandon any form
of violence, said French Foreign Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine and Fischer will meet with the U.N. civil administrator
in Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner, and the commander of the U.N. Kosovo
Peacekeeping Force (KFOR) Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
They will also meet with the chief of Kosovo Liberation Army (
KLA) Hashim Thaci, the Kosovo Albanian moderate leader Ibrahim
Rugova, the chief of the Serb Orthodox Church Monseigneur Artemije,
and the leader of the Movement of Serb Resistence Momcilo
Trajkovic.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers will also visit the headquarters of
French and German troops serving in KFOR in Kosovska Mitrovica and
Prizren, located in north and south Kosovo respectively.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio-Television Luxembourg on Tuesday,
Vedrine said that the U.N. is far from completing its peacekeeping
task in Kosovo and that he will tell the KLA that it must disarm
itself completely. (France-Germany-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Operations at the Hong Kong International Airport
were gradually returning to normal following Sunday's accident
involving a China Airlines MD-11 aircraft, the Airport Authority
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Billy Lam, chief executive officer of the Airport Authority,
said airlines had agreed where possible to provide larger aircraft
and more flights to help ease congestion at the airport, and that
the backlog of flights was expected to be cleared within the next
two days.
</P>
<P>
Lam said the Airport Authority had asked various airlines to
deploy more staff and flights to help these stranded passengers.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Authority would continue to provide whatever
assistance airlines needed to better serve passengers, he noted.
(China-Hong Kong-Airport)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Splitting rebels of the the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) announced Tuesday that they agreed to sign the
Lusaka Peace Accord as a group, Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The impasse was broken Monday night by the proposal of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) summit held last
week in Maputo, Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit, also attended by major supporters of the
rebels, Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu and his Ugandan
counterpart Yoweri Museveni, proposed that all the 51 founding
members of the main rebel party, the Congolese Rally for Democracy
(RCD), will sign the agreement as a group instead of one person
as initially proposed.
</P>
<P>
"We have accepted the proposal following the meeting of
founding members Monday night,'' one of the rebel leaders, Bizima
Karaha told RNA in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
Karaha disclosed that the proposal was accepted after they were
convinced to agree with it by the visiting South African Foreign
Minister, Nkosazana Zuma, and the Rwandan Minister in the
President's Office, Patrick Mazimhaka.
</P>
<P>
The rebel movement split in May of this year when Ernest Wamba
was removed from the RCD leadership by the founding members, and
then went to Kisangani to establish its own headquarters. (Congo-
Democratic-Peace Accord) 
</P>
</TEXT>
