<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Okays Refiner's Debt-Restructuring Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday
approved a draft plan to restructure the 2.17-billion-U.S.-dollar
debts of refinery company Thai Oil, a Government House press
release said.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the state-owned Petroleum Authority of Thailand
(PTT) was asked to inject 350 million dollars of capital into Thai
Oil so that it could maintain its current 49.9-percent stake in
the refiner.
</P>
<P>
Thai Oil had asked its 124 creditors to swap about 350 million
dollars' worth of loans for restructured equity and to extend the
maturity of its debt by 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Industry Minister Suwat Liptapallop said that Thai Oil has held
talks with most creditors on the principle of the restructuring
plan.
</P>
<P>
However, the company still needs to further negotiate with
Japanese banks, which are its biggest creditors, on the plan.
</P>
<P>
Thai Oil, which runs a 220,000-barrel per day refinery, saw its
debt soar after the baht fell sharply in July 1997. The company
has since November 1998 suspended debt repayments pending debt
restructuring talks with creditors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
