<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungry Dogs Raid Somali Village Killing One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A group of hungry wild dogs
attacked a Somali village, killed a person and wounded 11 others
in Lower Shabelle region of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The raid lasted for about one day starting Monday afternoon and
 continued to 11:00 a.m. (local time) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mukhtar Ali Gesey, a businessman in the town, told Xinhua that
the dogs have rushed out from around a large rain-created water
pool near the village. More than eight dogs were seen running
wildly on the sandy streets chasing and attacking people, he said.
</P>
<P>
The biting dogs stripped away all the muscle below the knee of
a boy who is selling toothbrush sticks near a market.
</P>
<P>
Bulo Marer village, about 120 Km south of the capital on the
road to the southern port town of Kismaio, has no hospital or
doctor available. Local elders began treating the wounded
voluntarily with self-assigned pharmacies and organized a group of
young militiamen to fight against the dogs.
</P>
<P>
Two of the dogs were killed Tuesday. One of the elders in the
village said that none of the people has so far caught the rabies
the dogs may be carrying.
</P>
<P>
The town returned to calm in the afternoon, but local people
still carry guns or batons for self-defense.
</P>
<P>
Local people said the dogs had probably had nothing to eat and
this could have been a strike against hunger. The Somalis do not
own or feed dogs out of religious reason.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in a year that dogs attacked parts of
Lower Shabelle region controlled by faction leader Hussein
Mohamed Aidid. Early last year, a similar attack stormed the town
of Qoryoley wounding several people, four of whom were known to
have caught rabies 20 days later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Woman Remembers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year is the 50th anniversary of the People'
s Republic of China (PRC). Xinhua News Agency is releasing a
series of stories about Chinese men and women, young and old, to
present a picture of the changes that have taken place in China
over the past 50 years. The people will describe their own
experiences and how they fit into the changes in the motherland.
This is the second article.
</P>
<P>
HEFEI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Ma Maojie clearly remembers the
day she ferried the first group of People's Liberation Army
soldiers across the Yangtze to fight the Kuomintang troops, 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze separated the Communist area from the Kuomintang
area in 1949 and on April 20 of that year, Mao Zedong attacked
suddenly using thousands of small boats.
</P>
<P>
Ma, who was 15, and her brother, ferried the first 30 soldiers
in the assault wave at night. The flames reflected off the river,
she recalls, and the roar of cannons almost made her deaf. Several
of the boats were hit by shells or intercepted by Kuomintang ships,
but Ma's boat continued on its way.
</P>
<P>
As they approached the bank, she suddenly felt a sharp pain in
her right arm. It came from a bullet, but she just continued
paddling and got all the soldiers to the beachhead. The first boat
to reach the south bank.
</P>
<P>
She carried two more loads of boats before daylight and many
more people and weapons over the next several days. The Kuomintang
troops were strong, but could not keep up with the PLA, Ma says,
and several days later, the PLA took Nanjing, which was the
Kuomintang capital, meaning the collapse of the regime.
</P>
<P>
Six months later, Mao Zedong declared the founding of the
People's Republic on the Rostrum of Tian'anmen Square and the end
of the Kuomintang after a four-year civil war. The remaining
Kuomintang troops fled to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Ma was given a medal and called a hero and her boat was
christened "The First Ferry to Carry Soldiers across the Yangtze".
When asked why she wasn't scared to death, she says plainly: "I
was born to a poor family and my four sisters died of illness or
hunger. My father was enlisted in the Kuomintang army and I was
sold to a man as a wife for three baskets of rice." If the PLA
hadn't come, she says plainly, she would have died.
</P>
<P>
Because she was a hero, Chairman Mao invited her to the
founding ceremony of the People's Republic on October 1, 1949, but
she didn't go because she was too young, she says ruefully. And,
her parents were also afraid of the journey to Beijing. They
thought it was at the end of the horizon and nobody could come
back from there.
</P>
<P>
Today they all have TV sets and newspapers telling about
everything in the world, she explains, but then people had little
access to information, But, in 1951, when Mao sent a second
invitation, the girl started off.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, she watched theatrical performance seated between
Chairman Mao and Premier Zhou Enlai. Mao asked her what her name
was and she answered tensely: "I have only the family name Ma.
Villagers call me 'sister'," and Mao said: "How can a hero have no
name?" The next day she ate with Mao and his family. Mao gave her
a pen and a notebook and wrote a few words in it, calling her "
Maojie." He had given her a new name, " Maojie", or "Sister of the
Mao family".
</P>
<P>
Ma has five children and she and her husband live a peaceful
life in east China's Anhui Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Arctic Expedition Slightly Disoriented by GPS Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China's first Arctic
expedition, which is doing research in the Arctic Ocean, had a
slight malfunction in its global position system (GPS) but no
serious problems.
</P>
<P>
The satellite clock memory was out of sync and could have
caused some operation problems in the GPS. That was on Monday and
some satellites had a problem, but the expedition was not
seriously affected. The new GPS being used by the expedition was
operating well, according to Qin Weijia, assistant to the chief
scientist in charge of coordinating research projects on the ship,
the Snow Dragon.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the Arctic Ocean is complicated and visibility
is usually limited to 100 meters on foggy days, so they rely
entirely on GPS. "It's hard to imagine the consequences if some
GPS instruments failed," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
But, for safety's sake, the expedition suspended some
operations for the day and the Snow Dragon stayed close to the
temporary ice station. In the past week, the expedition did
research on a floating piece of ice and the nearly 20 GPS
instruments were key instruments.
</P>
<P>
Ocean currents and winds could change the position of the Snow
Dragon and the temporary observation station from time to time,
and a temporary station could float many kilometers from the
expedition boat overnight. Both people and equipment could be left
missing without any precise idea about their position. The ship's
boat and helicopter could also get lost.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Manage to Find 68,000 Fugitives From Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Public Security
Ministry officer said today that by August 20, more than 68,000
fugitives had been rounded up in a nationwide campaign to find
people at large that began July 1.
</P>
<P>
Of the 68,000 fugitives, 43,000 were on National Fugitive
Information Network files, including 198 of the most-wanted, said
Deputy Minister of Public Security Bai Jingfu.
</P>
<P>
The three-month campaign is aimed to eliminate possible trouble
and create a better environment for the 50th anniversary
celebration's of the People's Republic and for the return of Macao
to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The officer asked various areas and police units to work
shoulder to shoulder to make the campaign more effective.
</P>
