<HEADLINE> UNICEF Increasing Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) today issued a report saying that although China has
achieved a great deal it still needs to make a great community-
based effort to help handicapped children and to stop trafficking
in women and children as well as to improve nutrition, health, and
education.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on UNICEF's next five-year plan here, its China
representative, Edwin Judd, said that the organization will make a
joint effort with the Chinese government to reach China's goal set
in 1990 and will discuss cooperation for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF, which will develop with China new modes of helping
handicapped children in the coming five years, spent two million U.
S. dollars in China during the 1996-1999 period and helped 5,000
children in 25 municipalities, provinces and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
It will also cooperate with the Chinese government in reducing
infant mortality rates and developing health care for mothers and
infants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
