<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Joint International Force to Protect War Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to sign
protocol to protect victims of international armed conflicts, a
senior official was quoted by the Thai News Agency (TNA) as saying
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Armed Forces are studying carefully the Additional
Protocol I of the 1949 Geneva Convention, to determine who should
be classified as "war victims" and whether some certain groups,
like separatists, should be included before signing the protocol,
Vasin Teeravejayarn, director-general of Thai Foreign Ministry's
Department of Treaties and Legal Affairs, said.
</P>
<P>
The official also said that Thailand will not sign Additional
Protocol II to protect victims of non-international armed
conflicts because the Thai Armed Forces opposed to the offering of
protection to domestic armed groups and separatists.
</P>
<P>
According to both codes of ethics, civilians, soldiers wounded
on the battlefield and prisoners-of-war must all be treated
humanely, while the torture and execution of those considered war
victims is prohibited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
