<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chairman of Thai State-Run Bank Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of state-owned Krung
Thai Bank (KTB) of Thailand Mechai Viravaidhya resigned Monday,
saying his resignation will provide an opportunity for a more
suitable person to do the job.
</P>
<P>
Mechai and five other board members proposed their resignations
at an emergency meeting of the board of the Financial Institution
Development Fund (FIDF), the majority shareholder of KTB.
</P>
<P>
Mechai's resignation came amidst increasingly heated argument
between the government and the opposition on the KTB issue.
</P>
<P>
Mechai has been accused of conspiring to discredit Finance
Minister Tarrin Nimmannahaeminda by leaking a confidential
auditors report, which revealed that KTB was saddled with about 84
percent of non-performing loans (NPL) and would need provisions of
364 billion to 394 billion baht (9.8 billion to 10.6 billion U.S.
dollars) to cover the potential losses.
</P>
<P>
However, KTB, the largest bank of Thailand, said its NPLs were
59.3 percent at the end of June, no higher than the average level
of Thai banks.
</P>
<P>
The KTB issue, directed against Sirin Nimmannahaeminda, former
KTB president and the younger brother of the finance minister, has
been politicized and thus threatened the stability of the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
