<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thorpe Shine as More Records Fall at Pan Pacific Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian teenager Ian Thorpe
became swimming's newest star as he established his third world
record in as many days at the on-going Pan Pacific swimming
championships in Sydney on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
American Lenny Krayzelburg also set a world record in the men's
100 meters backstroke -- the sixth in three days at Sydney's
Olympic pool.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Thorpe lowered his own 200 meters freestyle
mark to one minute 46.00 seconds in Tuesday's final, just 24 hours
after he set the previous mark of 1:46.34 and two days after he
shattered the 400 meters freestyle world record.
</P>
<P>
Krayzelburg, a Ukranian-born American, sliced more than a
quarter of a second off the previous 100m backstroke world mark
set by American Jeff Rouse at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics,
clocking in 53.60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Penny Heyns won the women's 100m breaststroke in
1:07.08, but was not happy with her performance a day after she
broke her own world record in the heats.
</P>
<P>
The dual Atlanta Olympic champion has set an amazing five world
records in the past five weeks but ran out of steam in Tuesday's
race.
</P>
<P>
Mai Nakamura brought about Japan's first gold medal of the
championships after a dead-heat finish with Australian Dyana Calub
in the women's 100m backstroke.
</P>
<P>
Australian Michael Klim, the reigning men's 200m freestyle
world champion, was under Thorpe's world record pace at the 100m
point, but he was unable to keep up when the teenager kicked away
for a new world mark.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe said he would attempt to lower his record even further
on Wednesday by swimming the lead-off leg in the Australian 4x200
meters freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
The Australians keep the world record they set at last year's
Commonwealth Games in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
Their team also includes Grant Hackett, who had held the 200m
individual record before Thorpe shattered it on Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the third day competitions, Australia have won
five of the six gold medals in the men's events while the U.S.
have a sole one through Krayzelburg. The 23-year-old reigning 100
and 200m backstroke champion had never set a world record.
Krayzelburg was 0.35 seconds under Rouse's seven-year-old record
after the first 50 meters and he held on to clip 0.26 off the mark
by the end of the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
