<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assets of Closed Thai Finance Firms Sold at 3.9 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has fetched 146.8
billion baht (3.9 billion U.S. dollars) from the sales of core
assets of defunct financial companies, the Financial Sector
Restructure Authority (FRA) said in a report available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The FRA said that core assets seized from 56 closed financial
companies were valued at 584 billion baht (15.8 billion dollars).
The authority organized six auctions to sell the assets, which
raised about a quarter of the valued assets.
</P>
<P>
The FRA said U.S.-based investment bank Goldman Sachs was the
biggest winner, taking assets worth 208.9 billion baht (5.6
billion dollars), followed by the Asset Management Corporation of
Thailand, which won assets worth 188.9 billion baht (5.1 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
After the financial crisis broke out in mid-1997, the Thai
government closed 56 ailing financial companies. The FRA was then
set up to sell off the assets of these companies.
</P>
<P>
According to the FRA, 72 percent, or 6,364 employees, had been
laid off during the closure of the financial firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
