<HEADLINE> World's Top Players Enter Hong Kong Squash Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It's a huge event in its own right and it is the most
important thing for me here to win this event," said Peter Nicol.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, all of the world's top 24 players, except
injured world number seven Derek Ryan of Ireland, have made it to
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region for the Open, one of
the eight-event World Super Series.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Barada of Egypt, now ranked third in the world, was fully
stretched before securing a second round berth by an hard victory
over Australian Billy Haddrell, winning 15-9, 9-15, 15-11, 8-15
and 15-5.
</P>
<P>
World No.5 Martin Heath of Scotland defeated Mark Chaloner of
England 15-12, 15-13, 9-15 and 15-7.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Canad's world champion and world number one
Jonathon Power, together with two Britons, world number four Paul
Johnson and number six Simon Parke, will show their skills
respectively in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
The 32-draw open is sanctioned by the Professional Squash
Association (PSA) and is one of the PSA world tour which contains
50 events this year. 
