<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Needs to Effectively Utilize Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Water Resources
Ministry has been urged to make a master plan for effective use of
water resources in the country.
</P>
<P>
Drawing a master plan of water resources is conducive to
efforts geared to ensure the realization of food self-sufficiency,
representative of the ministry Kidane Assefa said in a paper
presented on Tuesday to a panel discussion on "Drought and
Climatic Changes in Ethiopia".
</P>
<P>
Kidane said that the uneven water distribution in Ethiopia has
hindered the efficient utilization of the country's water
resources.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, described as "reservoir of Africa", is well known for
its plentiful natural water resources.
</P>
<P>
However, only 200,000 of the three billion hectares of
irrigable land in the country has so far been developed through
irrigation, Kidane said, noting that no more than 17 percent of
the country's population have had access to clean water.
</P>
<P>
The figures, he said, are very minimal when compared with that
of other sub-Saharan countries.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia loses three billion tons of soil worth about 250
billion birr (nearly 31 billion U.S. dollars) annually due to
erosion, the representative said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
