<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Delegation Arrives in Pakistan for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Taliban's top foreign
affairs official Mullah Muhammad Hassan, heading a high-level
delegation, arrived here Tuesday for a three-day official visit to
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Hassan will hold talks with his Pakistani counterpart Sartaj
Aziz on various issues including the bilateral relations between
the two countries, with focus on the controversy over the Afghan
Transit Trade Agreement (ATTA).
</P>
<P>
The ATTA, signed in the 1960s, was aimed at facilitating the
foreign trade of Afghanistan which has no sea port. Under the
agreement, the inland country only pays a meager amount of service
charges for the transit trade through Pakistan and enjoys
exemption of duties.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan imposed restrictions on the ATTA in 1997, dropping 36
items from the list of duty-exempted goods, arguing that most of
the goods imported under the ATTA were not used in Afghanistan but
made their way back to the Pakistani markets.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, goods smuggled into Pakistan
are depriving the national exchequer of over 5.5 billion rupees
(about 100 million U.S. dollars) every year mainly due to the
exemption provided to Afghanistan under the ATTA.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan Taliban are unhappy about the "unilateral
restrictions" by Pakistan on the Afghan transit trade and have
been calling for the removal of the restrictions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
