<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Moves to Better Education Conditions in Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has began to
carry out a program in some poor areas that need extra investment
in education, the Education Department announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The program involves the implementation of a 5 billion pesos
(125 million U.S. dollars) worth of school building and
rehabilitation work for poor communities in several provinces,
Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Education Secretary Andrew Gonzalez said the ongoing program
will benefit the provinces of Antique, Guimaras, Benguet, Ifugao,
Leyte, Agusan del Sur and Zamboanga del Sur.
</P>
<P>
These provinces belong to a cluster of more than 20 poor
provinces that are covered by a flagship project for basic
education called Third Elementary Education Project (TEEP), he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Gonzalez, the new classrooms constructed under the
project, partly funded by the World Bank and the Japan-based
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF), are now being used in
Antique province.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary Victor Manhit said the 125-million-dollar fund
for new school construction and rehabilitation is part of the
16.9-billion pesos (420 million dollars) fund of TEEP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
