<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Makes Efforts to Fight Tuberculosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's health care service
cured 38,700 tuberculosis (TB) patients and detected more than
40,300 new cases in the first six months of this year, Vietnam
News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
TB control has been considered one of the priorities in health
care development in Vietnam, according to Director of Vietnam's
National Institute of TB and Lung Diseases (NITLD) Nguyen Viet Co,
who was briefing an international training course on TB treatment
opened in Hanoi Monday on Vietnam's TB control efforts.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese government pledged to provide sufficient medicine
for TB treatment. It allocated 22 billion Vietnamese dong (nearly
2 million U.S. dollars) to the National TB Control Program this
year.
</P>
<P>
Since its launching in 1957, Co said, the National TB Control
Program has been expanded to cover 99 percent of the population
now.
</P>
<P>
NITLD's statistics show that the national rate of TB
contraction is 69.6 per 100,000 and an estimated 130,000 people
contract the disease every year. Curing rate among patients
undergoing short-course chemotherapy is estimated at between 88-89
percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of TB cases is likely to increase in connection with
the spread of HIV infection, said Co, adding that at present, more
than 1,270 TB patients are reported to carry HIV, accounting for
almost 11 percent of the total number of HIV-positive cases
detected so far.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam currently has nearly 400 doctors, more than 600 nurses
and about 560 testing technicians working for the TB control
program at district level and almost 8,000 medical workers being
involved at commune level.
</P>
<P>
The on-going international training course on TB control in
Hanoi is organized by the NITLD in coordination with the World
Health Organization (WHO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
