<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planned Aluminum Smelter Threatens Iceland's Highlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The planned aluminum smelter in
Reidarfjordur on Iceland's East Coast would result in enormous
costs to the environment of the highlands, the World Wide Fund for
Nature (WWF) said.
</P>
<P>
"Cheap electricity for aluminum production is no justification
for ignoring environmental considerations," said the international
conservation organization in a press release received here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a conference held last week, WWF said that Norsk Hydro,
mainly owned by the Norwegian state, declared it would continue
with plans to build new aluminum smelters in countries such as
Iceland to provide cheap energy.
</P>
<P>
"Environmental accounting should not be a concept alien to an
international firm," said Peter Prokosch, director of the WWF
Arctic Program in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
"If Norsk Hydro engages in building and running an aluminum
smelter in Eastern Iceland, it will also be responsible for the
inevitable destruction of the largest wilderness area remaining in
Western Europe," he warned.
</P>
<P>
"Large parts of the unique Icelandic Highlands will have to be
flooded to produce the energy required," Prokosch said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
