<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rural Areas Undergoing Historic Changes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By 1998, over 95 percent of villages across the country had
access to highways, some 70 percent to telephone services, and
more than 95 percent to electricity.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in lifestyle has prompted the growth of
democratic awareness on the part of farmers, over 90 percent of
whom are actively participating in the direct election of
villagers' committees.
</P>
<P>
Farmers who used to care only about their own grain harvest
have also begun to take interest in and even directly involve
themselves in the management of village affairs.
</P>
<P>
A sociologist said that the democratic rights farmers enjoy
from their autonomy are bound to bring greater social changes in
China, just as the right to farm their own land after 1978 has
done.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the dramatic changes in the country's rural
areas to the central government's consistent policy of putting
agriculture above everything in developing the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The household contract responsibility system with remuneration
linked to output, which symbolized the beginning of China's reform
and opening up, has kindled millions of farmers' enthusiasm for
production.
</P>
<P>
And the introduction of agro-sciences featured by seedling
projects, plastic sheeting and water-saving techniques has further
promoted the rapid growth of agriculture, contributing 40 percent
to the sector's growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rural Areas Undergoing Historic Changes (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With improved productivity and a rapid growth of grain output,
a considerable number of farmers and agricultural workers are free
from being tied to the land and can either go to find jobs in
cities or set up enterprises locally.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Ministry of Agriculture said that 15 percent
of the 80 million farm workers in cities nationwide return home
every year, having learned new techniques and the latest farming
information and often with spare cash in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
What is more important is that they bring home these new ideas
and concepts, which have boosted overall progress in the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of township enterprises has come as a
great surprise for most Chinese people as they have not only
improved the overall quality and efficiency of the rural economy
but also played an important role in the growth of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that one third of the nation's gross domestic
output, one fifth of the nation's tax revenue and one third of the
nation's exports come from township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, these enterprises have employed more than 100
million surplus rural laborers, contributing considerably to the
growth of income in the sector.
</P>
<P>
But agricultural experts warn that China has every reason and
need to step up its agricultural development because by 2030, the
nation's population is expected to reach 1.6 billion and an
additional one-third more of the present day grain output will be
needed to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a sustainable, steady and healthy development of
agriculture, China is spending heavily on such agro-scientific
projects as the Harvest and Bridging programs, while stepping up
protection of farmland and the ecological environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
