<HEADLINE> U.S. to Reinforce Diamond Traffic Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States has promised
to reinforce control on the international illicit diamond traffic,
which supports various conflicts in Africa, including the Angola
civil war, said the U.S. Embassy in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The embassy was quoted on Tuesday by Jornal de Angola as saying
that the U.S. government has maintained contacts with Angolan
entities and Robert Fowler, head of the Commission of Sanctions
for Angola, in a bid to find the best way to reinforce the control
on the illicit flux of diamond.
</P>
<P>
U.S. government has realized that the "blackmarket" constitutes
a factor of causing the unstabilization in Africa, proportionating
arms transactions and profound entrance of international criminal
organizations into regions in conflicts, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique issued recently by the State
Department, the U. S. government will discuss the situation of the
illicit traffic with principal diamond-producing countries,
including Angola.
</P>
<P>
U.S. admitted it is difficult to identify the diamonds from
Angola among all the precious stones entering U.S., but said that
the priorities given by the new policy will change the situation,
according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
