<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Krayzelburg Breaks 100m Backstroke Swimming World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ukranian-born American clocked a time of 53.60 seconds to
shatter the previous world mark of 53.86 set by Jeff Rouse at the
1992 Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Krayzelburg was 0.35 seconds under Rouse' record pace after 50m.
He held on to slice 0.26 seconds off the previous mark at the end
of race.
</P>
<P>
Krayzelburg said although a world record had been set a goal
for the championships, he was surprised with that time. His world
record was the sixth world mark set in two days at Sydney's
Olympic pool, the venue for the 2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
Winner of both the 100m and 200m backstroke titles at the 1997
Pan Pacs in Japan, Krayzelburg took out the double at last year's
world championships in Perth, but not in world record time.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old is also looking to claim the 200m backstroke
record in Sydney after posting the second fastest time ever in
Minneapolis a fortnight ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
