<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Draft Law on Maritime Lawsuits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of maritime
lawsuits and a lack of legal solutions have impelled China's
legislative body to create a new maritime law.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee
convened here today to discuss a draft of ad hoc procedures for
maritime lawsuits, which will be subsidiary to the Maritime Law
that went into effect in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the necessity of the draft, Li Guoguang, vice-
president of the Supreme People's Court, described the draft law
as vital to ocean shipping, foreign trade and better use of
maritime resources of China, which boasts a large ocean territory
and the fifth biggest shipping industry in the world.
</P>
<P>
"A surge of admiralty actions in recent years makes it highly
necessary to formulate a maritime law for handling lawsuits in
accordance with both China's situation and international practice,
" Li said.
</P>
<P>
Admiralty courts across China have heard more than 25,000
maritime cases since 1984. Among these, 3,746 are related to
foreigners from 73 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The existing Maritime Law is too difficult to be implemented
due to the lack of a procedure law, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 12-chapter draft stipulates that the law is applicable
within the territory of the People's Republic of China, and that
foreigner-related cases will be tried in accordance with the law,
international treaties participated by China, and international
practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
