<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Current Account Back in Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa slipped back
into a current account deficit equivalent to some 0.5 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP) in the second quarter from a surplus
of above one perfect of GDP in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
In its Annual Economic Review, the South African Reserve Bank
(SARB) said the current account at seasonally adjusted, annual of 13 percent rea
ched in the fourth quarter last
year.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's gross foreign reserves rose by more than five
billion rand (830 million U.S. dollars) in the first half due to
net capital inflows of 7.4 billion rand, and the repayment of 2.1
billion rand in foreign credit lines, as well as valuation
adjustments of 250 million rand.
</P>
<P>
This meant the import coverage of reserves rose to 12 weeks at
the end of June from 10 weeks at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The SARB said export volumes had risen by 4.1 percent in the
first half of 1999 compared with a rise of 3.1 percent in 1998 as
Asian economies recovered.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in foreign reserves meant the real effective
exchange rate of the rand rose by 3.4 percent in the first half of
1999 compared with a decline of 14.1 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The employment situation in the private sector seems to be
improving since the middle of 1998 and in the first quarter of
1999 there was a 2.4 percent annualized increase in employment on
the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Average nominal remuneration per worker eased to a 7-percent
growth rate in the 12 months to end March 1999 from 10.7 percent
in 1997. This, the SARB, said augured well for future declines in
inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
