<HEADLINE> Japan Shares Gold at Pan Pacific Swimming Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A timing malfunction meant the electronic scoreboard first
showed defending champion Nakamura winning the race in a time of
one minute 1.51 seconds despite a last-gasp burst from Calub.
</P>
<P>
But after several minutes of confusion, the umpires reviewed
the video back-up clock and decided the two had dead-heated.
</P>
<P>
Barbara Bedford of the United States took bronze in 1:01.76,
just ahead of Nakamura's rival Noriko Inada.
</P>
<P>
Nakamura, surprised by the timing malfunction, expressed
disappointment at not being able to match or beat her personal
best.
</P>
<P>
Calub, 23, came from third to first in the dying seconds of the
race, cutting more than 1-1/2 seconds off her previous personal
best. 
