<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Courts Executed Over 3,000 Court Rulings In Media Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua)-- In the latest week-long media
campaign on law-enforcement, Chinese courts have issued more than
3,000 rulings involving some 200 million yuan (about 24 million U.
S.dollars), the Supreme People's Court (SPC) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
 The SPC said in the nationwide media drive against local
interference in and resistance to the enforcement of court rulings
that the courts across the country have effectively tackled the "
law-enforcement difficulties."
</P>
<P>
These courts publicized the names of enterprises which have
refused to honor their debts, and seized, froze, distributed or
sold the property of debtors who have some means of paying off
debts but intentionally evaded court orders, the SPC said.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin Municipality held public hearings to conduct legal
education for those who refused to honor their obligations, and at
the same time closed 187 cases involving some 28 million yuan .
Forty debtors who had resisted the court orders were arrested.
</P>
<P>
Li Lingshu, an official of Zibo City's Real Estate
Administration Bureau, was detained according to law by the Higher
People's Court of Shandong Province for resisting to assist the
enforcement of court rulings during the campaign, the SPC
confirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
