<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Liquidator Oversees Eaton's Selloff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Boston-based U.S. Gordon Brothers
Retail Partners LLC has been hired to liquidate all the
merchandise of Canada's oldest retailer, T. Eaton Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The Globe and Mail newspaper reported Tuesday that under an
insolvency plan approved by a court Monday, a Gordon affiliate,
Retail Funding Inc., has bought Eaton's entire debt of 189.6
million Canadian dollars (about 126.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Retail Funding has agreed to inject 100 million Canadian
dollars (about 66.7 million U.S. dollars) into Eaton's to keep
stores operating during the liquidation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Brothers announced Monday that it has a team of 120
employees ready to move in to the stores to manage the liquidation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Eaton's said it aims to have its last store
locations cleared out and closed by November 30, gradually putting
all its 13,000 employees out of work.
</P>
<P>
The 130-year-old collapsing retailing empire also said it will
negotiate with other retailers to find buyers or new tenants for
its 64 stores.
</P>
<P>
Customers are rushing to the Eaton's stores across the country
for liquidation sales, only to be disappointed at the usual price
tags. The expected selloff is yet to start in a couple of days
until the end of November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
