<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Leone Ex-Rebel Leader to Tour West African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Former rebel leader of Sierra
Leone Foday Sankoh is scheduled to visit Burkina Faso, Cote
d'Ivoire and Liberia before taking up his duties in a new
government of national unity in his country seven weeks after
signing a power-sharing accord with the government.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh who is to head a commission for post-war reconstruction
and mineral resources in the new government returned to Togolese
capital of Lome at the weekend from Libya, which has been accused
in the past of providing military support to the rebels,
according to a Vanguard report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted him as saying "I went to Libya to say thanks
to (President Moamer) Kadhafi for his country's mediation in the
peace process. "
</P>
<P>
Sankoh said that before heading to Freetown next week, he
planned to go to Burkina Faso, Cote d'Ivoire and finally to
Liberia where he would "hold an audience with good friends" in
these countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his arrival in Freetown had been delayed by
security and accommodation problems, adding the government had
not even set up an office yet for his post, which is to be equal
in rank to that of vice president.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
had already submitted a list of its nominees for four cabinet
posts and four deputy ministerial positions, and President Ahmad
Tejan Kabbah would announce the new cabinet "shortly".
</P>
<P>
For the last two weeks, a four-man RUF delegation has been in
Freetown preparing for the RUF's entry into the new government,
which was supposed to have been set up in late July under the
Lome peace agreement signed on July 7 between the government and
rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
