<HEADLINE> Singapore to Transfer Ownership of Suzhou Industrial Park to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is planning to
transfer a major part of the ownership of the Suzhou Industrial
Park, a joint Singaporean-Chinese development project that began
in 1994, to the Chinese side, according to George Yeo, Singapore's
Minister for Trade and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Yeo made the remark at a press conference here this afternoon
where he said that Singapore's shares will go from 65 percent to
35 percent as of January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Singapore's Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien
Loong and his Chinese counterpart Li Lanqing will meet in
September to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the park, in Jiangsu Province, east
China, has had 135 projects with 38.5 billion U.S. dollars worth
of investment, 130 of them industrial projects worth 33.2 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singaporean business people still have confidence in China's
economic potential, Yeo said, and transferring ownership won't
affect relations between Singapore and China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
