<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Rallies Support for Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada, who is on a three-day tour in Mindanao, southern
Philippines, called on the local residents Tuesday to back
economic reforms by amending the 1987 Constitution, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inauguration of major agriculture projects,
Estrada said their support would help the government bring in the
foreign capital needed to improve domestic industries and other
capital-intensive sectors through the proposed Charter changes.
</P>
<P>
Economic reforms, which reportedly dominate the planed charter
amendment, include relaxing restrictions on foreign ownership of
land and equity in certain public utilities and businesses to pave
the way for the inflow of more foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
This initiative, however, met strong domestic opposition which
was highlighted by the August 20 mass rally in Manila led by
former president Corazon Aquino and Manila Archbishop Jaime Sin.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that he is ready to consult with all
sectors on the charter change and defer to their final decision on
the matter, adding that he owes this to the people who elected
him.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Estrada also called on Mindanao residents to
restore and maintain peace and order in the region so as to help
accelerate the region's development.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign capital will come in if investors have a sense of
security," Estrada stressed.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said, he would continue to go around Mindanao to make
sure the government continues to provide them with food, shelter
and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Mindanao is the second largest island in the Philippines, which
boasts of rich natural resources but has been lagging behind in
the nation due to social disorder stemming from ethnic conflicts
and rebellion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
