<HEADLINE> Sensex Up in Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The sensitive index rose 62.32
points Tuesday on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) in the wake of
sustaining buying by operators coupled with Institutional
supporters to select counters.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-30 share sensitive index opened remarkably higher at
4762.72 and moved in a narrow range of 4770.91 and 4745.48 in 75
minutes of trading before closing at 4792.10 against Monday's
close of 4729.78, netting a gain of 62.32 points.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-100 index also went up by 27.03 points to 2164.06 from
previous close of 2137.03.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 index and the Dollex were quoted remarkably up at
498.38 and 190.70 compared with last weekend close of 492.28 and
188.33 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-500 index improved further by 17.82 points to 1477.95
from Monday's close of 1460.13.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that the market is now in the grip of bull
operators and the Sensex is likely to cross the previous all time
high of 4810.88 achieved on July 15, 1999, in couple of days.
</P>
</TEXT>
