<HEADLINE> Son of Syrian President Concludes Visit to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Bashar Hafez Al-Assad, the
son of Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad, left here Tuesday for
Saudi Arabia after wrapping up his first visit to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Bashar, who arrived here late Sunday, held separate talks
with Kuwaiti Emir Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, and acting Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah on ways
of developing bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The meetings also touched upon regional and international
issues which are of interest to both countries, the official news
agency Kuna reported.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Bashar, 34, asserted Syria's supportive stance
toward settling the issue of Kuwaiti and third country's
nationals allegedly held in Iraqi jails.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Kuwaiti, Syrian and Lebanese families of
detainees in Iraq at the Kuwaiti National Committee for Missing
and POWs, the Syrian official criticized the continuous detention
of those people, stressing that "Damascus stood and will stand by
Kuwait to solve the issue."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait insists that Iraq is still holding over 600 Kuwaiti
and third country nationals since its invasion of the Gulf
emirate in 1990. But Baghdad denied the Kuwaiti allegation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
