<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels to Sign Cease-Fire Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Splitting rebels of the the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) announced Tuesday that they
agreed to sign the Lusaka Peace Accord as a group, Rwanda News
Agency (RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The impasse was broken Monday night by the proposal of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) summit held last
week in Maputo, Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit, also attended by major supporters of the
rebels, Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu and his Ugandan
counterpart Yoweri Museveni, proposed that all the 51 founding
members of the main rebel party, the Congolese Rally for Democracy
(RCD), will sign the agreement as a group instead of one person
as initially proposed.
</P>
<P>
"We have accepted the proposal following the meeting of
founding members Monday night,'' one of the rebel leaders, Bizima
Karaha told RNA in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
Karaha disclosed that the proposal was accepted after they were
 convinced to agree with it by the visiting South African Foreign
Minister, Nkosazana Zuma, and the Rwandan Minister in the
President's Office, Patrick Mazimhaka.
</P>
<P>
The rebel movement split in May of this year when Ernest Wamba
was removed from the RCD leadership by the founding members, and
then went to Kisangani to establish its own headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Initially each rebel faction of the RCD claimed legitimacy to
sign on behalf of the rebel movement, while only one signature was
reserved for the Congolese rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The solving of this legitimacy problem between the two
Congolese rebel factions engaging in bitter power struggle has
been hailed as a last chance to rescue the peace deal which risked
to derail if the rebels did not endorse it.
</P>
<P>
But regional analysts believe that the signing of the Lusaka
peace deal by the rebels will not resolve the pending issues,
notably the military aspects, relating to the implementation of
the accord.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
