<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Air Force to Update its Fighter Fleet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to sell off three types
of combat jets in its air force and buy new multi-role fighters to
replace them, reported a Nigerian newspaper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Air Staff Isaac Alfa announced in Lagos that the
aircraft to be sold are the MiG (Mikoyan - Guverich) 21 and 15
series, the Sepe Cat Jaguar and the G222. "Anyone interested in
buying them should come," the Guardian, a major Nigerian newspaper
quoted the Air Vice-Marshal as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force has about 20 MiG aircraft, including some
two-seater MiG 214 for strike interceptor roles. It has about four
MiG-15 UTIs, MiG15 Fagot, now retired, MiG 17, MiG 21 Fish bed and
MiG 21U Mongol, reported the paper.
</P>
<P>
By selling out the old MIG planes, the Nigerian Government will
be clearing its air force of Soviet-supplied combat jets.
</P>
<P>
To take the place of the aircraft, the government has decided
to procure more advanced multi-role fighters for the Air Force
from the west.
</P>
<P>
It was only after the inauguration of Obasanjo administration
that the United States and other western countries had relaxed
their arms sales to Nigeria. The Nigerian government currently is
seeking closer cooperation with the United Sates, and a group of
military experts are reportedly already in Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Rebel Faction to Reconsider Position on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A faction of the rebel
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) has agreed to reconsider its
position on the July 10 Lusaka cease-fire agreement aimed at
ending the war in the Democratic Republic of Congo. In a
telephone interview with Xinhua, South African Foreign Minister
Nkosazana Zuma's spokesman Kangalane Hlongwane could not confirm
reports that both factions of the RCD have agreed to sign the
Lusaka accord.
</P>
<P>
He said after the shuttle diplomacy by Zuma at the weekend, the
RCD faction led by Emile Ilunga has agreed to go to its founding
members in the constituencies to decide on the matter.
</P>
<P>
He said after that the rebel faction would communicate with the
 Organization of African Unity on their decision.
</P>
<P>
"At this time we have to wait," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hlongwane said Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, who leads the other RCD
faction, has been persuaded by Uganda to sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
A leadership squabble has kept the two factions from signing
the Lusaka document, signed by Congolese President Laurent Kabila,
together with five other countries involved in the year-old
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Wamba dia Wamba, who was ousted as RCD leader in May, has
insisted that he should sign the agreement, but the new leader,
Ilunga, said he would not sign it if Wamba dia Wamba does.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola were allies of Kabila, and Uganda
and Rwanda, who sided with the RCD in their fight to topple
Kabila, later supported the two factions respectively.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is supporting Wamba dia Wamba while Rwanda is supporting
Ilunga.
</P>
<P>
Zuma returned home Monday after traveling to the RCD base in
eastern Congo, Goma, and Rwanda and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand Sign Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Thailand Tuesday
reached two agreements on the exemption of visa for holders of
diplomatic and official passports and on cultural cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A press release of the Myanmar Foreign Ministry said the
agreement on visa exemption was signed by Myanmar Foreign Minister
U Win Aung and his visiting Thai counterpart Surin Pitsuwan on
behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
Surin arrived here Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The cultural agreement was signed by Myanmar Minister of
National Planning and Economic Development U Soe Tha and Surin.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed after the conclusion of the 5th
meeting of the Myanmar-Thailand Joint Commission for Bilateral
Cooperation (JCBC), co-chaired by the two foreign ministers, the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
In December 1997, foreign ministers of Myanmar and Thailand
agreed at the 4th meeting of the JCBC held in Bangkok to enhance
bilateral cooperation in the sectors of culture, health,
education, technology, agriculture, tourism, trade, investment,
communications, energy, fishery and drug control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
