<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supplying Aircraft for UNITA Comes from Ukraine: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The airplane carrying arms for
the National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
stopped by the Zambian government on August 19 was from Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Official news agency Angop quoted diplomatic sources as saying
that the plane capable of transporting heavy arms has been in
Lusaka, capital of Zambia, the east neighbor of Angola, for five
days.
</P>
<P>
The crew members of the plane, now detained by the Zambian
government, were found living in a hotel in Lusaka, according to
Angop.
</P>
<P>
The private aircraft was rented by somebody with an aim to rush
arms for Jonas Savimbi, head of the rebel UNITA, said Angop.
</P>
<P>
But the previous reports said that the plane belongs to Kenyan
company "Meridien Air Nairobi" and came from Banqui, capital of
the Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
Embargos on military and petroliferous materials, prohibition
of journey abroad, closing representative institutions in other
countries, financial sanctions and the interdiction of diamond
export are included in the sanctions against UNITA imposed by the
Security Council of the United Nations in 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to the Security Council, any individuals,
institutions or countries violating the sanctions will be taken to
the tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
