<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Implement World's Biggest Coastal Reclamation Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's coastal
reclamation project in the northern state of Kedah, reportedly
the biggest in the world, is ready to take off as it has been
given Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) approval by the
Department of Environment, Kedah Chief Minister Sanusi Junid said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The privatized reclamation project could be implemented anytime
now depending on the capability of the developers concerned, he
said in Alor Setar, the state capital, according to Bernama news
agency.
</P>
<P>
The project approved by the federal government in June 1997 was
held back by the economic downturn and also because its macro EIA
studies had not been approved yet.
</P>
<P>
The coastal reclamation project at a proposed cost of 30
billion ringgit (7.894 billion U.S. dollars) will involve 20,390
hectares of coastal areas facing Malacca Strait covering a
110-kilometer stretch from Kuala Sanglang to Kuala Muda of the
state.
</P>
<P>
Among the developments slated under the project to be
implemented in two phases are the Northern Region International
Airport, an industrial area, a port, a power generating station,
housing facilities, resorts and recreational centers.
</P>
<P>
It is scheduled to be implemented through packages and the key
developers listed include Samudera Baru Darul Aman, Sayak Beach
and SKS Venture.
</P>
<P>
"We will maintain the developers which have been selected and
others which are interested in the project are encouraged to send
their quotations to the state government," the chief minister
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the state government had received quotations from
Japanese and European companies which were keen to rent out or
sell machinery for the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
