<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Calls for "Six Plus Two" Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The anti-Taliban opposition
alliance Tuesday called for the involvement of "Six plus Two"
group in seeking settlement of the Afghan issue, saying Pakistan
could not be viewed as "an impartial broker".
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for Pakistan to undertake such a project
alone when it can be implemented under the auspices of the 'Six
plus Two' group of nations," Hussain Anwari, member of the
opposition alliance said in a statement from Tajikistan received
here.
</P>
<P>
"The United Front delegation once again declared its support to
the 'Six plus Two' (Afghanistan's six immediately neighbors plus
Russia and the United States) initiative," Anwari said.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistani delegation led by Secretary of the Interior
Ministry Rustam Shah traveled to Dushanbe, capital of Tajikistan,
Monday for the second round of talks with representatives of the
anti-Taliban alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani delegation held talks with the anti-Taliban
alliance in Dushanbe last week. The same team went to Kandahar,
headquarters of the Taliban, last Saturday to brief the Taliban
leaders of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani team presented a new proposal to the opposition
alliance during the second round of talks in Dushanbe saying the
proposal will be presented to the Alliance Supreme Leadership
Council in the coming days, according to Anwari.
</P>
<P>
The final decision will rest with the Alliance Supreme
Leadership Council, said Anwari. He, however, did not give any
details of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report from Kabul quoted anti-Taliban spokesman
Abdullah as saying, "The talks (between Pakistan and the
alliance) failed because the Pakistanis did not offer anything
new, nor could they prove in practice that they were impartial
peace mediators."
</P>
<P>
He said that the opposition alliance would not hold further
talks with Pakistan until it took practical steps to end its
"military" support to the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the shortcut to peace in Afghanistan is
cessation of Pakistani aid to the Taliban and despatch of
reinforcements of troops and volunteers to our country," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has dismissed the allegations by the
anti-Taliban opposition as "malicious and baseless".
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, which launched its latest peace initiative last week,
said the aim of its renewed peace efforts was to help the warring
Afghan factions engage in negotiations to restore peace to
Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
