<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni: Uganda, Rwanda Not Fighting for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has said that the recent clashes between Ugandan and
Rwandan troops in the Congolese city of Kisangani were not fought
for the control of the city as previous reports had said.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the government's daily New Vision, which reached
here Tuesday morning, Museveni explained that there was no
full-scale battle in Kisangani, the third largest city of the
Democratic Republic of the COngo.
</P>
<P>
"There was no battle for Kisangani; but there were armed
clashes in Kisangani. These clashes were mainly in the center of
Kisangani. The street battles in Kisangani could not have been for
the control of Kisangani in a military sense," he said in the
letter.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, it was not for the control of Kisangani because to
do so, you do not need to control buildings in the center of town
but to control the two airports, the river transport and the roads
into and out of Kisangani," the 54-year-old president added.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that the clashes in Kisangani between the
two allies could have developed into the battle for Kisangani
unless a cease-fire had been reached in time.
</P>
<P>
He said Ugandan troops in the city were to provide protection
for rebel leader Wamba dia Wamba and to ensure the verification
exercise by South African and Zambian ministers.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan troops, who were lightly armed and had little
ammunition as they were not deployed for battle, were attacked by
sizeable Rwandan force operating in the city, Museveni said.
</P>
<P>
The four-day clashes between the two armed forces in Kisangani,
which started on August 14, had led to a loss of over 200 lives
and more injuries.
</P>
<P>
Museveni and Rwandan Vice President and Defense Minister Paul
Kagame met in western Uganda last Tuesday to hammer out a
cease-fire to prevent the escalation of the clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
