<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Needs 14,000 More Police Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambia police service is
understaffed by at least 14,000 officers, making it difficult for
the service to combat the escalating crimes, according to Times of
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted police spokesman Alex Chilufya as saying
Monday that with the Zambian population of about 10 million there
is need to have a minimal number of 27,000 policemen.
</P>
<P>
Currently there is only 13,000 policemen and women, which means
that one officer caters for about 730 people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chilufya said it is important to recruit more policemen if the
crime is to be curbed.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the police service is facing some other
major hurdles like lack of transport, which makes it difficult to
follow up any reports.
</P>
<P>
The police command of the country has set a deliberate policy
to reach the 27,000 establishment by 2005, he said.
</P>
<P>
The police also needs modern and effective communication
equipment, he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman urged the government to definitely look into the
plight of the policemen because their current conditions of
service leave much to be desired.
</P>
<P>
The crime cases such as armed robberies have been increasing in
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, a group of gunmen snatched 248,000
U.S. dollars last week from seven foreign tourists about 100
kilometers southeast of Lusaka in broad daylight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
