<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy Relaxes Visa Requirements for Kenyans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan tourists and businessmen
visiting the United States for a "short" period will be exempted
from visa requirements, the U.S. embassy in Nairobi has announced.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard daily quoted the embassy's Consul
General Kay Anske as saying that the move was taken to encourage
more Kenyans to visit the U.S.
</P>
<P>
However, Anske did not specify how many days there are in a
short period.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the new embassy has more space than the former one
bombed by international terrorists last year, she said that more
visa applicants can be served within a shorter time.
</P>
<P>
Anske added that students with all the required documents will
receive a visa within a day.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy was attacked on August 7 last year by a car
bomb, which killed more than 250 kenyans and 12 Americans and
injured 5,000. The U.S. government abandoned the devastated old
embassy and spent about one year to build a new one.
Consular operations at the new embassy started Tuesday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
