<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Allow 10,000 More Palestinian laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- As another conciliatory
gesture towards the Palestinians, the Israeli government has
decided to allow 10,000 more Palestinian laborers into the country.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after Prime Minister Ehud Barak adopted the
recommendation by Israel's coordinator in the Palestinian areas
and security facilities.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator recommends the government loosen the age
restriction for Arab laborers entering Israel and increase the
quota of Arab businessmen entering Israel or traveling between the
West Bank and Gaza, the local daily Jerusalem Post reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rule, Arab workers without security violation
records will be allowed to enter Israel if they are married and at
the age of 21 or above. Previously, only those married workers who
are at the age of 23 or above could be allowed in.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to increase the number of Arab workers
entering Israel from the West Bank and Gaza Strip to some 80,000,
compared with the previous 70,000. The number of Palestinian
merchants allowed to enter Israel or to travel between West Bank
and Gaza increased by about 5,000, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to allow hundreds of Gaza
residents above 44 years old to worship at the Al-Aqsa Mosque
complex in the Arab East Jerusalem on Fridays. The number of
family unification permits was also increased, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Defense Ministry said these steps were aimed at
improving economic and social conditions of the Palestinians and
also in line with the government's policy to reduce the number of
foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
The new decision came a week after Deputy Defense Minister
Ephraim Sneh of the Labor Party said that Israel would increase
the number of work permits given to Palestinian laborers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry believes the country's security can be enhanced if
more Palestinians are earning livelihoods from jobs in Israel, the
Jerusalem Post said.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli defense officials, about 17 percent of
employed Palestinians from the West Bank and Gaza work in Israel,
but they earn over 40 percent of the total income in the areas.
</P>
<P>
In the last few weeks, the moderate Israeli government has
taken several goodwill gesture towards the Palestinians, including
opening a main street closed five years ago in the West Bank
city of Hebron and releasing a long-held Palestinian prisoner.
</P>
<P>
In their talks Monday, the Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
also reached an overdue deal on the construction of a seaport in
Gaza and the opening of a "safe passage" between Gaza and the
West Bank, which will help improve the economic situation in the
Palestinian areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Accuses Developed Countries of Flouting WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph
Kamotho has accused developed countries of failing to abide by the
agreements of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard daily Tuesday quoted Kamotho as
saying that Kenya has opened its markets like some other African
countries, and developed countries should reciprocate this gesture
by opening further their markets.
</P>
<P>
"WTO agreements having been in existence for four and a half
years, developing countries have not achieved any meaningful
progress in their exports because of the insincerity and
dishonesty of the developed countries," said Kamotho at a seminar
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kamotho noted that the implementation of the Uruguay Round of
WTO agreements have posed serious challenges to developing
countries because their needs, wishes and limits were not taken
into consideration.
</P>
<P>
Due to huge external debts and reduced international aid, WTO
must start focusing on the constraints of developing countries,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for technical assistance in capacity building,
product management and infrastructure from developed world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
