<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Industrial Production Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Israel's industrial production
during the first half of this year fell by 2.8 percent compared to
the previous six months, according to a report issued by the
Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bank of Israel left its benchmark interest rate
unchanged at 11.5 percent when it Monday announced the monetary
policy for September, saying it is necessary to keep the inflation
under control.
</P>
<P>
The industrial production figure, based on preliminary figures,
declined by 0.8 percent compared with the first half of 1998. The
number of salaried workers and work hours were down 2.5 percent
from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
But the quarterly figures showed that the economy might be
rebounding from the bottom of a slump. While the industrial
production in the first quarter declined by 2 percent, the second
quarter saw a 1 percent increase, both in comparison with the same
period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rise in the second quarter, Bank of Israel Governor
Jacob Frenkel announced Monday that he would keep interest rates
unchanged in September. Central bank officials said that the
decision stemmed from a need to temper inflation.
</P>
<P>
Twelve-month inflation is expected to reache about 5.4
percent, higher than the 3-4 percent target the government set for
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Prospects of a rate cut weakened after the consumer price index
rose by 0.3 percent in July, higher than expected. The Bank of
Israel was also concerned that declining interest rates would
further weaken the Israeli currency shekel, which dropped to a
nearly nine-month low against the dollar this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
