<HEADLINE> Courier Knocked out in Opening Round of Pro-Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Seventh-seeded Jim Courier of
the United States lost to 60th-ranked Sargis Sargsian of Armenia 6-
4, 6-4, in the opening round of the U.S. Pro-Tennis Championships
in Brookline, Massachusetts on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Courier and Sargsian, who both live in Orlando, Florida, have
been frequent practice partners.
</P>
<P>
Actually, Sargsian's serve had a lot to do with his success
against the 36th-ranked Courier. He lost only 14 points on serve
in the match and served the last three games at love.
</P>
<P>
Fourth-seeded Cedric Pioline of France and eighth-seeded Jonas
Bjorkman of Sweden were easy winners.
</P>
<P>
Pioline, No. 1 in France and a two-time Grand Slam finalist,
beat Argentine Gaston Gaudio, 6-4, 6-0 while Bjorkman edged
Slovakia's Jan Kroslak 6-2, 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
Also advancing to the second round was sixth-seeded Marat Safin
of Russia, a 7-5, 7-5 winner over Italy's Gianluca Pozzi.
</P>
<P>
In other matches, France's Arnaud Clement defeated Slava
Dosedel of the Czech Republic 3-6, 7-6 (7-1), 6-2; Australia's
Andrew Elie, who was leading Romanian Andrei Pavel, 6-3,1-0, when
Pavel retired with an elbow injury; and American Cecil Mamiit
ousted Costa Rican Juan Antonio Marin, 7-6 (7-1), 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
