<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Teng-hui's "Two States" Remark Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Visitors to the Museum of
Historical Data on Li Zongren, located in Zaozhuang City in east
China's Shandong Province, have expressed indignation at the
recent "two states" remark by Taiwan leader Lee Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
Most have written their criticism in the guest book,
complaining of Lee's separatist statement and praising Li Zongren'
s patriotism as a former general of the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
Hu Yousong, Li's widow, said that her late husband's beliefs
oppose Lee's remark and that no Chinese would agree with him.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that when Li was critically ill, he wrote to the late
Chinese leaders Mao Zedong and Zhou Enlai, saying that the people
of Taiwan would only have a bright future if Taiwan returned to
the embrace of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
A Taiwan visitor, surnamed Hui, said that all Chinese should
learn from Li Zongren and make efforts to assist the reunification
of the motherland as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
A Hong Kong visitor named Zheng said that the reunification of
the motherland is the common desire of all Chinese on both sides
of the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Li Zongren successfully commanded the Battle of Taierzhuang
against Japanese invaders in 1938 at Taierzhuang, a location of
strategic importance in Zaozhuang.
</P>
<P>
Li was elected vice-president under the Kuomintang rule in 1948.
He returned to Beijing in 1965 and issued a statement promising to
devote his life to the reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The museum opened in April and has received hundreds of
visitors daily.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
