<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Confers with Brunei Sultan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today
told visiting Hassanal Bolkiah, the Sultan and head of state of
Brunei Darussalam, that he will attend the third informal meeting
between leaders from the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (
ASEAN) and leaders from China, Japan and the Republic of Korea,
scheduled to be held in Manila, Philippines, in November.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remark in a meeting with Brunei Sultan Hassanal
Bolkiah here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said that China attached importance to its cooperation with
ASEAN member states and such cooperation had witnessed rapid
progress and a good momentum. He also said that mutual
understanding and trust had been enhanced thanks to the ever
frequent contacts between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"The informal meeting is a good mechanism and a creative move
for concerned countries to develop cooperation for common growth,"
he said, adding that it also plays an important role in
strengthening mutual understanding and trust and cooperation
between countries and in promoting regional stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
"China is willing to make more efforts to ensure the success of
this informal meeting and cooperation throughout the whole East
Asia region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Discussing Chinese-Brunei relationship, Zhu said that he
believed the Sultan's visit will give an impetus to the growth of
bilateral friendly and cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique, which was published Monday, delineated
the framework for future cooperation and reflected the consensus
of the two country's highest leaders, according to Zhu. "The
Chinese government will make every effort to implement the goals
set out in the document," he added.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that there is great potential yet to be tapped
between China and Brunei in economic and trade cooperation. "
Brunei boasts rich resources and China has the willingness to
expand its cooperation in all fields," he said.
</P>
<P>
Brunei's Sultan told Zhu that he was impressed by China's
achievements made in economic growth in this second China trip.
Compared to what he saw in 1993, China has obviously enjoyed even
greater development, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed appreciation for China's efforts in expanding
friendly relations with ASEAN and extended congratulations to the
Chinese government and people for the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
