<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law Amendments to Combat Worsening Air Pollution in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China's national legislature
is considering new dramatic changes to the law on the control of
air pollution, despite the fact that it was only revised three
years ago, in a bid to tackle the foul air which is affecting
people's health and the country's overall economic development.
</P>
<P>
"Draft amendments tabled today suggest banning the discharge
of air pollutants beyond a certain level and imposing heavy fines
for those who contravene the regulations," Qu Geping, chairman of
the Environment and Resources Protection Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), told lawmakers of the NPC Standing
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Such changes mark a noticeable change from the existing
practice that allows the discharge of pollutants with only small
fines even if they exceed the legal limits.
</P>
<P>
The draft amendments also target car emissions and dust from
construction sites which are slowly poisoning city dwellers,
causing respiratory problems and affecting people's eyesight on
dry days.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that a total of 21 million tons of sulfur
dioxide are emitted into the atmosphere in China, in addition to
14 million tons of smoke-filled dust along with 13 million tons of
powder-like particles as a result of industrial production.
</P>
<P>
"China is one of the most polluted countries in the world,"
Qu said, citing a World Health Organization (WHO) report which
pointed out that of the world's 10 most polluted cities, seven are
in China.
</P>
<P>
The foul air has caused public outcry from among the people
of all walks of life, and it is quite usual for Chinese
legislators to consider new changes to a law that was just amended
three years ago, analysts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Two States" Remarks Threaten Peace in Asia-Pacific Region: Article (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's stand on the matter has won the respect of the
countries in the Asia-Pacific region as well as the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The article says that denying the one China principle and
separating Taiwan from China would damage the peace and stability
in the Taiwan Straits as well as in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government is determined and able to protect its
sovereignty and territorial integrity, the article stresses.
</P>
<P>
Hegemony recently has taken a new role on the world stage, and
a new attitude of intervention has reared its head. But any force
in the world would have to consider the cost and risk it would
face should it interfere with the Taiwan issue, which is China's
domestic business.
</P>
<P>
Some Asian countries are now seeing a glimmer of economic
recovery after suffering a two-year financial crisis. Therefore
they prefer a peaceful and stable Asia-Pacific environment which
would hasten the economic recovery and sustainable development,
according to the article.
</P>
<P>
It says that with the resistance of people in both China and
the Asia-Pacific region, Lee Teng-hui's separatist scheme to
damage the Taiwan people's interests and the peace of the Asia-
Pacific region is bound to fail.  
</P>
