<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law Amendments to Combat Worsening Air Pollution in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Statistics show that 70 percent of the 300 Chinese cities
under environmental surveillance are graded at "level three" or
beyond of the established pollutant standards for their air
quality which concerns Chinese officials as "level 2" is
internationally recognized as just about "suitable for human
existence".
</P>
<P>
"To achieve the results required by the legislation will be
a costly exercise," Qu said, pointing out that in the next 10
years, 180 billion yuan ( 21.77 billion US dollars) will be needed
to free 175 cities from the acid rain and nearly 150 billion yuan
(18 billion US dollars) for cleaning up the haze which affects 47
major cities.
</P>
<P>
Over the next ten years China also needs to spend 0.3
percent to 0.7 percent the value of its gross national product to
install mufflers in various industrial and social sectors. "
Meanwhile, urban real estate developers will have to spend 0.15
to 0.35 percent more on their projects to keep dust particles from
floating through the streets," Qu added.
</P>
<P>
"However," he claimed, " if this money is well spent the
benefits will be enormous. "
</P>
<P>
The discharge of major pollutants should decrease year by
year after controls are imposed and the air quality in major
cities is likely to improve significantly, he said. "The public
will be more than pleased if the amendment is adopted and enforced.
"
</P>
<P>
"In addition to the economic benefits generated by green
industries, people will be able to see a clear blue sky and
breathe fresh air and spend much less time seeing doctors," Qu
told the lawmakers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
