<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Conference on Hadron Spectroscopy Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The 8th International Conference
on Hadron Spectroscopy, sponsored by the Institute of High Energy
Physics (IHEP) under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
The conference is held every two years for the professionals in
hadron spectroscopy research, an important branch of high-energy
physics. Major topics to be discussed at this year's conference
include the interaction between hadrons, the physical properties
of hadron, and studies on hadron spectroscopy.
</P>
<P>
The electron positron collidor and the Beijing spectrometer,
which were developed by the Chinese Academy of Sciences, have many
advantages in carrying out experiments on hadron spectroscopy, and
have attracted large groups of scientists from the United States
and other countries planning to use it for scientific research,
said Huang Yinzhi, a research professor from IHEP.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 foreign scientists and 60 Chinese scientists will
exchange the latest results in hadron studies at the four-day
meeting. The conference will also give young scientists in China
the opportunity to learn more about developments in the
international hadron physics circle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Legislature to Review Nine Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China's highest legislative
body, the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (
NPC), opened its week-long session here today with nine
legislative bills scheduled for deliberation.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, presided
over today's opening meeting.
</P>
<P>
A draft amendment to the Personal Income Tax Law, proposed
by the State Council and tabled at today's meeting, suggests that
the words "interest from deposits and savings" be deleted from
items listed for exemption from personal income tax.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng told the lawmakers that
the measure is intended to stimulate domestic consumption and
invigorate the slack market demand. A vote will be taken when the
legislative session concludes on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The draft laws on solely-funded enterprises and public
bidding, which drew close attention of personalities from the
economic circles and were presented for further review today, are
also expected to be adopted during this session.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts say that the legislation for private
businesses will be of great significance to the Chinese economy,
just as significant as the late veteran leader Deng Xiaoping's
policy of household responsibility system was to the country's
vast rural reform of the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Three other bills were submitted today: the draft
regulations on supervision over major legal cases in adjudication
and prosecution work; draft amendments to the air pollution
prevention law; and a draft law on the ad hoc procedures of
maritime lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, draft laws on maritime environment, weather
services, and accountancy, which had been deliberated on and
revised earlier, were again presented to the lawmakers for
further deliberation.
</P>
<P>
According to the agenda adopted today, another bill set
forth by the State Council proposing an increase of national debt
for fixed-asset investment and an adjustment to the central
government's budget will be explained to the lawmakers on Saturday
and ready for a vote by Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
