<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Cracks Down On Public Bidding Loopholes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to curb shoddy
construction projects, China's highest legislative body, the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, plans to
revise the relevant law affecting the building sector.
</P>
<P>
A new draft of the Law for Inviting and Submitting Tenders has
been submitted for review to the eleventh meeting of the Ninth NPC
Standing Committee, which opened here today, to regulate public
bidding.
</P>
<P>
"Parts of the law have been changed in a bid to halt
corruption which arises in the course of public bidding," said Gu
Angran, vice-chairman of the NPC Law Committee, who explained the
proposed amendment to the NPC Standing Committee members.
Malpractice and low transparency in inviting and submitting
tenders are blamed as a major cause of poor quality construction
in China.
</P>
<P>
The draft stipulates that all large scale infrastructure and
public projects which are thoroughly or partially funded by the
state, international organizations or foreign government loans
have to undergo public bidding which will cover the survey and the
design and the construction of projects, as well as quality
inspection and purchase of major equipment and materials.
</P>
<P>
Administration officials will be prohibited from interfering
with the bidding. They will face disciplinary action such as
demotion or dismissal if they contravene the rules.
</P>
<P>
The draft also highlights the responsibilities of bidding board
members and outlines the penalties for offenders, such as the
confiscation of bribes and incorporating fines as high as 500,000
yuan (60,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said that the draft law will be probably approved at this
current meeting since it has twice undergone revision and its
feasibility confirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislature to Supervise Major Misjudged Legal Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- In a move to curb judicial
corruption, the National People's Congress, China's highest
legislative body, may give itself and local legislative bodies
jurisdiction over major legal cases which have been improperly
handled.
</P>
<P>
A provisional draft on related regulations has been submitted
to the ongoing session of the Ninth NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The new supervisory powers cover the major misjudged cases and
illegal activities of judges and law enforcement officers, which "
have tremendous negative impact on society and were not solved on
time," Hou Zongbin, chairman of the Civil and Legal Committee
under the NPC, explained to the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Violators are subject to severe punishment, including recall,
and serious cases will be "investigated and prosecuted for their
criminal liability according to law," the draft said.
</P>
<P>
The draft regulations also stressed that the supervision must
be exercised by the legislature as a group and not by individuals,
and jurisdiction must never be used to interfere with the
legitimate, independent rights and normal operation of the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Judicial supervision greatly concerns the general public, and
Li Peng, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, always attaches
great importance to it, Hou Zongbin said. He added that the draft
will create foundations for the formulation of a "supervision law.
"
</P>
<P>
The draft was formulated by the Civil and Legal Committee in
accordance with direct instructions issued by the NPC Standing
Committee, and based on wide-range investigation and consultation.
</P>
<P>
Hou said the fight against judicial corruption needs both an
internal supervision system handled by judiciary bodies and the
outside supervision of legislatures.
</P>
<P>
In the past ten years legislatures have managed to correct some
misjudged cases, which has helped to promote justice, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
