<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Formulates Action Plan for Mariculture Industry Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has formulated an
action plan to ensure the proper and sustainable development of
the mariculture industry, a senior official of the Fisheries
Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The plan advocates the concept of aquaculture development areas
under the greater context of coastal zone management, Mohamed
Mazlan Jusoh, director-general of the Fisheries Department, said
at a conference on mariculture and the environment here.
</P>
<P>
Marine-based aquaculture activities have been regulated through
the Mariculture Regulation 1990 and the Fisheries Department has
recently drafted a comprehensive set of Aquaculture Regulation
covering both land and water based activities.
</P>
<P>
Three different codes of practice for shrimp farming, marine
fish culture in cages and fish hatcheries have been developed to
serve as guideline for mariculturists, he said.
</P>
<P>
Suitable areas are identified and allocated for aquaculture use
while the Fisheries Department avoided mangrove clearings for
shrimp farming, especially in peninsular Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Unproductive agricultural land with access to brackishwater or
seawater and coastal belt with no mangroves are presently the
preferred sites for shrimp farming development, Mazlan said.
</P>
<P>
He said technical development would need to be balanced by
environmental considerations and this would require the legal
framework to achieve the ideal blend for sustainability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
