<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia to Demobilize 2,000 Soldiers in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 24 (Xinhua) -- At least 2,000 soldiers will
be demobilized later this year for the start of an effort to
eventually reintegrate 40 percent of Cambodia's total military
personnel into local communities, according to Tuesday's Rasmei
Kampuchea (Light of Cambodia).
</P>
<P>
The government is conducting a nationwide registration of
soldiers for the purpose of creating a real registration system by
eliminating ghost soldiers and of demobilizing a total of 55,000
soldiers by year 2003 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The effort, directly tied to the money received from donor
countries, is being coordinated by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The pilot demobilization will begin in December and the
demobilized soldiers and their families will be reintegrated into
communities of their choosing in Kampot province.
</P>
<P>
All will be given a one-year transitional period provided with
money, food, shelter and educational and vocational training. Job
counseling and placement will follow a soldier's settling down in
a community, and local authorities will be in charge of providing
land, according to World Bank officials.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the pilot demobilization project will cost
roughly 4 million U.S. dollars while the full-scale project will
cost 100 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
