<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka, Delhi Differ on Definition of Duty-free Access Products: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Ministry has handed
over a list of 25 Bangladeshi products to India for consideration
of their duty-free access to the Indian market, but there seems to
be divergence of views on the products list, an English newspaper
here reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The list, which was handed over to the Indian High Commission
in Dhaka last week, has been passed on to New Delhi for
examination, The Independent daily said.
</P>
<P>
During official talks in New Delhi in May this year, Indian
Commerce Minister R.K. Hedge assured his Bangladeshi counterpart
Tofail Ahmed that the Indian government would seriously consider
to allow duty-free access to 25 export products of Bangladesh to
help reduce the bilateral trade imbalance which is heavily in
favor of India.
</P>
<P>
While the Bangladeshi side maintained the definitions of a
product with its wider application, the Indian side was reportedly
taking a narrow view on it, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Indian High Commission officials in Dhaka had indicated that to
them the 25 products meant only 25 export items, a view also
shared by the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and
Industry, a source said.
</P>
<P>
By 25 products, Bangladesh meant 25 broad categories of
products, each of which could have many individual items under it.
The products list that Bangladesh handed over to India had roughly
more than 200 items, belonging to 25 broad categories of products.
</P>
<P>
Given the volume of trade imbalance and the wide range of
Indian export to Bangladesh running up to thousands of items, the
offer of zero tariff to only 25 items as indicated by the Indian
side hardly makes any sense, the source said.
</P>
<P>
India should not take a narrow view of the list and should show
goodwill to Bangladesh at a time when the government in Dhaka was
taking a greater risk while considering opening of transshipment
facility to India through Bangladesh, he said.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Tofail Ahmed declined to comment on the
divergence of views on the products list, saying he would not lend
credence to speculations.
</P>
<P>
The list of the 25 products includes artificial flower, ceramic
products, cosmetics and toiletries, electrical goods, electrical
cables and wires, furniture, jute and jute goods, knitwear,
leather products, plastic products, pharmaceutical products,
prepared food, tea, textile fabrics, and woven ready-made
garments.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh imports from India stood at 755 million U.S. dollars
during the 1997-98 fiscal year, while its exports to that country
were valued at 50 million dollars only, resulting in a huge trade
deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
