<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Considers Penalties Towards Dishonest Accountants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Accountants jailed for drawing
up false returns will be banned from re-entering the profession in
China, according to the draft accountancy law submitted to the
current session of the top legislature today for review.
</P>
<P>
Others whose certificates are revoked for breaking professional
ethics, including forging accounts, embezzling or misappropriating
company funds, but not yet punishable by the criminal law, will be
barred from practicing for at least five years, the draft
amendment stipulates.
</P>
<P>
These revisions have been introduced to curb the practices of
forging statistics to evade taxes, defraud banks of loans and
cheating the government, lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
According to legal experts, in the past quite a few companies
in China, as worldwide, used to maintain two sets of accounts: one
depicting actual turnover and figures and another for taxation
purposes. But today, some have been found to have up to four or
five.
</P>
<P>
However, most false accounts are compiled at the instruction or
instigation of managers or other executive officials, the
lawmakers pointed out.
</P>
<P>
To counter the situation, the draft law has included
administrative penalties for officials responsible and stipulates
that those whose deeds constitute a crime will be punished
according to the criminal code. 
</P>
