<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Minister Dismisses Charges of Aid Refusal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Health Minister Osman
Durmus, who has been under fire in the last two days for
allegedly turning down foreign aid to the earthquake-hit victims,
said Tuesday that his earlier statements had been misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
Some Turkish and foreign media reported that Durmus had told
health teams from the United States, Sweden, Romania and Greece on
Sunday that "we don't need any help."
</P>
<P>
"We're asking our hospitals to work under normal conditions
starting on Monday, because they are not overburdened," the
minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
This alleged statement has drew strong criticism from the
Turkish public as well as officials. Some have asked for his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
After a cabinet meeting on Monday, Durmus told reporters that
his earlier statements had been misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
"We need health equipment but not medicine. The foreign aid to
Turkey must be provided according to the needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports said embassies of foreign countries which
had dispatched rescue and medical teams to Turkey had told local
press that aid workers from their countries had been warmly
greeted by Turkish government officials.
</P>
<P>
The health minister also denied that there had been any
outbreaks of epidemics in the quake-stricken northwestern Turkish
regions, where over 14,000 people had been confirmed dead so far
in the 7.4-degree quake that occurred at 3:02 a.m. (0002 GMT)
on August 17.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of an outbreak of epidemic has been one of the
major concerns of the authorities since the pre-dawn killer
quake. A heavy rain soaking parts of the quake-hit regions Monday
aggravated their concerns.
</P>
<P>
Health officials are grappling with ways to block possible
spread of diseases like typhoid fever, cholera and dysentery.
</P>
<P>
Officials had sprayed disinfectants over stricken areas, dusted
purifying lime on rubble, roads and cemeteries while water
purification tablets had been distributed in some regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
