<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealanders Better Off After 10 years in APEC: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley said New Zealanders "are much better off as a result
of a more open and competitive economy."
</P>
<P>
She said this Tuesday when launching at the Parliament Building
the publication "APEC - 10 Years and Beyond", which contains a
collection of views from 10 prominent academics and business
people from around the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The authors, Prime Minister Shipley said, offer clearly the
view that "APEC is a force for the good of the region".
</P>
<P>
Shipley said statistics in the publication show that at the end
of 1997, New Zealand's economy (GDP) was worth 65 billion U.S.
dollars, compared with 44 billion U.S. dollars at the end of 1989,
 when the APEC was established.
</P>
<P>
Per capita, she continued, New Zealand's GDP was 17,317 U.S.
dollars at the end of 1997, compared with 13,213 U.S. dollars at
the end of 1989.
</P>
<P>
In the area of tariffs, Shipley said, substantial reductions
are occurring across the region. For example, she added, China's
tariffs have fallen by 57 percent on average, while the Republic
of Korea and Malaysia's have reduced by 59 and 43 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the importance of the Asia Pacific region to her
country, Shipley said: "70 percent of New Zealand's exports go to
the APEC region, and 70 percent of its imports are sourced from
the Asia Pacific. APEC economies also send New Zealand 70 percent
of its tourists. The jobs and well-being of New Zealanders are
inextricably linked with the Asia Pacific, and the health and
stability of the economies of the region. It is absolutely vital
for a small trading nation like New Zealand to engage with a
process like APEC."
</P>
<P>
Auckland, the biggest city in New Zealand, will be the venue
for this year's Informal Meeting of APEC Leaders, which is
scheduled for September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
