<HEADLINE> New Zealand Bank to Treble Fee for ATM Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Bank customers in New Zealand
can expect big rises in fees for using automatic teller machines
(ATM).
</P>
<P>
The Dominion Tuesday quoted an announcement of WestpacTrust,
New Zealand's biggest bank, as saying the bank would more than
treble ATM charges for its customers who use rival bank machines
from the present 25 cents of the NZ dollar (13.3 U.S. cents) to 85
cents of the NZ dollar (45 U.S. cents) in October.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper said it is likely other banks
would follow suit with similar fees to protest the use of their
ATMs.
</P>
<P>
"The move is seen by other banks as possibly the first salvo in
a war for automatic teller machine use," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
It also reported that WestpacTrust will also in October
increase fees for electronic transactions by 10 cents (5.3 U.S.
cents) to 35 cents (18.6 U.S. cents) and over-the-counter
transactions on check accounts from 50 cents (26.5 U.S. cents) to
65 cents (34.5 U.S. cents). 
</P>
</TEXT>
