<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Increase Police Presence in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand is sending its
extra military and police staff to East Timor, and its army is
preparing armored personnel carriers which may be sent later in
the year.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post Tuesday quoted New Zealand Foreign Minister
Don McKinnon as saying that more military officers and police
would be sent following next Monday's ballot on East Timor's
future.
</P>
<P>
Five Defense Force military liaison officers and 10 civilian
police officers are now serving with a large UN contingent in East
Timor, according to the Wellington-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
McKinnon was quoted as saying that a transition period of some
months will occur before the Indonesian Parliament can give
constitutional effect to the outcome of the ballot.
</P>
<P>
During this time, New Zealand will double to 10 the number of
military liaison officers in East Timor and increase the number of
civilian police officers to 15, the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
The UN plans to increase the civilian police force from about
280 to 460 and boost the number of military liaison officers from
50 to 300, according to him.
</P>
<P>
McKinnon said big hurdles remain, such as persuading all
parties to accept the ballot result without resorting to violence.
</P>
<P>
He urged Indonesia to redouble its efforts to ensure security
and calm in the post-ballot period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
