<HEADLINE> Manila to Review Agreements With Foreign Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine civil aviation
authority has ordered a review of the nation's agreements with
foreign airlines in a bid to protect interests of the Philippine
Airlines (PAL), Philippine News Agency (PNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Civil Aeronautics Board (CAB), the lopsided
air agreements entered between the Philippines and at least 38
foreign airlines stalled the rehabilitation program of the PAL and
cut its revenues drastically.
</P>
<P>
The PNA quoted CAB Executive Director Guia Martinez as saying
that of these 38 agreements, at least 11 have been confirmed to be
gravely disadvantageous to PAL.
</P>
<P>
She said as a result of these lopsided agreements, PAL lost
hundreds of millions of pesos.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts said that from 1993 to 1998, CAB took
unilateral action that damaged the national interest and
contributed significantly to PAL's near collapse.
</P>
<P>
The CAB readily granted the foreign airlines' requests to
increase their number of flights and seat capacity, but it failed
to get the same arrangement from their respective governments for
PAL, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
