<HEADLINE> Young Zimbabweans Interested In  AIDS Counselling, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 24 (Xinhua) -- More young Zimbabweans had shown
interest in voluntary AIDS counselling and testing, according to
the country's National AIDS Coordinating Program (NACP) and
Zimbabwe AIDS Prevention and Support Organization.
</P>
<P>
The NACP, which recently established the "New Start" voluntary
counselling and testing services at five centers in Harare,
Bulawayo, Chinhoyi, Triangle and Hwange, received inquiries from
many youths.
</P>
<P>
NACP Gender and HIV/AIDS Coordinator Janet Muteiwa said in the
daily Herald Tuesday that the enthusiasm shown was reflective of
what was going on nationwide.
</P>
<P>
There was an increase in the number of people wiling to know
their HIV status, she said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is second to Botswana on the world list of countries
worst affected by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
About 1.4 million adults, 25.8 percent of sexually active
adults aged between 15 and 49 are thought to be infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 people die every week from HIV/AIDS-related
illnesses. enditem

