<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad's Son: Hezbollah to Lay Down Arms After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The son of Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad, Bashar Assad, has said that Hezbollah will dismantle its
military wing following an Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon,
the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe its (Hezbollah) members will go back to normal life
and will choose other ways to serve their country after achieving
their long-cherished victory," said Assad, a reportedly political
heir apparent of his father, in an interview with the London-based
Arabic magazine Al-Wasat, which was also reproduced by the paper.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Muslim Shiite military group Hezbollah, or Party of
God, has been spearheading a guerrilla war trying to oust Israeli
forces out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Iran have been the principal backers of the group.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, Hezbollah has remained tight-lipped on its
long-term plans for the resistance.
</P>
<P>
This has made Israel hesitate to carry out a troops pullout
from the country for fear that its northern areas will be
attacked again after the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
However, few observers in Lebanon believe that Hezbollah will
continue its operations against Israel once the occupation has
ended.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Raad, who heads Hezbollah's parliamentary block,
hinted that the views of the party's leadership were close to
those of Assad.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the group told the paper that Hezbollah has
been preparing for the inevitable Israeli withdrawal and is
expected to switch its efforts to championing the cause of the
dispossessed Shiite community via Parliament and its substantial
social wing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
