<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 80,000 Babies Born with HIV Every Year in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Of the 400,000 deliveries that
occur in Zambia every year, about 80,000 are HIV positive, Zambian
Mother-to-Child Transmission Working Group has disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Co-ordinator of the group Chewe Luo said her organization would
try to reduce the number by 50 percent through the provision of
the AIDS drug AZT Zidovudine to infected mothers while receiving
66,400 U.S. dollars from the Japanese government for the purchase
of equipment and detergents to be used in the testing of expectant
mothers and their children.
</P>
<P>
Zambian newspaper, The Post, Tuesday quoted Luo as saying:"We
shall also make sure that we substitute infected breast milk with
formula milk to reduce the mother-to-child infection."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony held Monday, Japanese
Ambassador to Zambia Yoshihiro Nakamura said the negative impact
of the HIV infection on the human resources development of the
Zambian people demands that intervention measures be taken to cope
with the situation.
</P>
<P>
In order to give the best and appropriate care to expectant
mothers and their children, he said it is vital that they should
undergo testing that will give accurate results.
</P>
<P>
That was the only way the prevention of the HIV transmission
from mother-to-child could be achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
