<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Preparing to Face Global Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is preparing a
foundation through the merger of banks, brokerage and insurance
firms in order to face global competition, Second Finance Minister
Mustapa Mohamed said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the long term, Malaysia would not be able to avoid global
powers and "it is important for us to make these preparations so
as not to be submerged by the flow of liberalization and
globalization," he said when officiating at a seminar on
investment strategy here.
</P>
<P>
"One day, foreign investors would invest freely here and we
should also be able to grab investment opportunities in other
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Amidst this scenario, the government wants Malaysian companies
to be active participants, Mustapa said, adding Malaysian
companies should prepare themselves to become global participants
in line with the process of market liberalization and
globalization.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the government policy now is to reduce
investment overseas, this is only a temporary measure due to the
regional economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis has taught everyone in the region not to
practice herdlike investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa said it was important to initiate efforts to diversify
investments but the crisis has taught a lesson, namely, not to
rely only on the property sector or a particular sector.
</P>
<P>
He said that expertise in coming out with investment analysis
and quality needed to be enhanced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
