<HEADLINE> Indonesian President to Visit Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie will pay a one-day working visit to Malaysia Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Habibie will hold talks with Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad on bilateral issues and on the latest development in the
regional and international situation, Foreign Minister Syed Hamid
Albar told a press conference here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral matters, discussion may focus on illegal
immigrants, migrant workers, cooperation in education, haze
management and technical cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will also brief each other on the current
situation of their respective countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss on the continuing growth of ASEAN of which
both Malaysia and Indonesia are members.
</P>
<P>
Several ministers accompanying the Indonesian president will
have a joint meeting with their Malaysian counterparts, Syed Hamid
said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian president will also have an audience with
Malaysia's Supreme Head of State (King) Sultan Salahuddin Abdul
Aziz Shah.
</P>
<P>
Habibie's visit to Malaysia will be his second since his
assumption to the office. His first visit here was in November
1998 when he came to Kuala Lumpur for the APEC leaders' informal
meeting.
</P>
<P>
And his visit is a follow-up of the gathering between the
leaders of the two countries. Mahathir and Habibie met last in
Batam, Indonesia in May this year. 
