<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke082417 - Bangladesh High Court Orders Removal of Slum Dwellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A High Court Division of
Bangladesh's Supreme Court has ordered the government to remove
shanties set up in the court premises within 24 hours upon receipt
of the order, press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering the judgment on Monday, Justice Mohammad Fazlul
Karim said that the home minister, home secretary and the
inspector general of police should take measures to remove the
shanties.
</P>
<P>
"Remove them from the court compound and from in front of the
house of Dr. Kamal Hossain, otherwise we'll take serious and
strong view of the matter," Karim said. Hossain, an eminent
lawyer, was fighting the legal battle against the demolition of
slums.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise the law will take its own course," Justice Karim
said while disposing off a writ petition seeking a rule against
the government's eviction of slums from the city.
</P>
<P>
The division bench disposed of the writ petition without
issuing a rule and vacated the "stay" order issued earlier on
eviction of slums.
</P>
<P>
The petition was filed by some non-governmental organizations
and slum dwellers to challenge the legality and authority of the
demolition of slums and the eviction of inhabitants without
arranging alternative accommodation and without any prior notice.
</P>
<P>
The court said that the slums should be removed from the city
in phases under a rehabilitation program by the government. "It
has to be done phase by phase otherwise the demolition of slums
may not solve the problems," it said.
</P>
<P>
"We find that petitioners don't oppose the removal of slums
from the city if it's done under a rehabilitation scheme," Justice
Karim said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government asked the slum dwellers on Monday
night to vacate the Supreme Court premises by Tuesday, following
the judgment of the High Court Division.
</P>
<P>
The court asked the government on Sunday to evacuate the
squatting slum dwellers from their compound for the sake of
discipline and security at the county's highest seat of justice.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of evicted slum dwellers entered the Supreme Court
premises in central Dhaka last Wednesday night and built makeshift
homes there, refusing to leave the area until their demand of
immediate rehabilitation was met.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 70,000 people were evicted from the slums in the capital
city early this month by law-enforcing agencies, following the
killing a police constable. The government launched the eviction
drive on the ground that the slums had become dens of terrorists
and criminals.
</P>
<P>
It is said there are about 2 million slum dwellers in the
Bangladeshi capital, home for some 9 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
