<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senators Doubted of Conclusion of NBI Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate
investigators have aired doubts that the August 13 blast at the
National Bureau of Investigation (NBI) headquarters was accidental
as claimed by the bureau, the newspaper Today said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senator Robert Barbers, chairman of the Senate peace and order
committee conducting a separate inquiry into the blast, was quoted
as saying that he was not convinced by the bureau's findings and
would not rule out other possible causes at this time.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a prober's report declared the explosion that killed
seven agents and wounded several others inside the office of NBI's
Special Investigation Division (SID) was an "accident."
</P>
<P>
Other senators pressed the bureau to pursue all angles in the
blast, saying that the explosion, believed to have been caused by
various explosives stored inside the SID office, was not
accidental.
</P>
<P>
Senator Rene Cayetano claimed the explosion could not be
concluded as an "Act of God" or a fortuitous event, saying "the
fact that a sizable amount of explosives seized by the NBI since
last year had not been turned over to the Firearms and Explosives
Office and remained in custody constitutes gross negligence on the
part of the NBI."
</P>
<P>
Senator Aquilino Pimental urged investigators to check the
possibility that the blast may have been "criminally instigated."
</P>
<P>
According to NBI lawyer Sasai Fiji, a volunteer witness claimed
to have seen someone lob an unknown object on the roof of the SID
building moments before the explosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
