<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voting Result in E.Timor to be Announced in New York, Dili: U.N. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations, organizer of
the August 30 direct autonomy ballot in East Timor, will announce
simultaneously the voting result in New York and Dili, capital of
East Timor, about one week after the popular consultation, a U.N.
official said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan himself will announce the
result, spokesman of the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) David
Wimhurst said in Dili Monday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said a total of 451,792 people have registered
for the ballot, reports reaching here from Dili said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the vote counting would be conducted in Dili and only
one result would be announced.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an influential political party, the Forum for Unity
proposed to conduct vote counting in the polling stations. It
warned that intransparency in vote counting could become a reason
for either or both of the two conflicting groups in East Timor to
reject the ballot's outcome.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMET is planning to set up 700 ballot stations across
East Timor. The consultation is meant to let the East Timorese
people indicate whether they accept or reject wide-ranging
autonomy within Indonesia's fold. If they vote against autonomy,
the Indonesian government will let the territory get independence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas here Monday
expressed his rejection to the proposal for the sending of a U.N.
peacekeeping force to East Timor, saying it was personnel opinion
from a few U.S. Senators.
</P>
<P>
Last week, some U.S. senators who visited Dili, proposed to
send a U.N. peacekeeping force to Dili because violence had been
increasing recently.
</P>
<P>
"It's their business, their personnel opinion, not the U.S.
government official stance," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
He said any party could have its own opinion about East Timor,
but Indonesia's internal policy on the issue would not be
influenced by it.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the security situation in East Timor has continued
to improve although minor instances of violence occurred here and
there.
</P>
<P>
However, Indonesian Defense and Security Minister General
Wiranto said earlier that he would have no objection to the
assignment of more U.N. civilian police in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, the Indonesian government agreed to offer
wide-ranging autonomy for the East Timorese people through a
direct ballot. On May 5, Indonesia, Portugal and the United
Nations decided to hold the ballot in August.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
about 15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until
1975. It became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the U.N. never
recognized the move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Endemic Fauna, Flora Endangered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- About 75 percent of Sri Lanka's
endemic species of fauna and flora face the threat of extinction,
said a latest study by the International Union for the
Conservation of Nature (IUCN).
</P>
<P>
The IUCN has compiled in its study a list of nationally
threatened species of Sri Lanka in consultation with a wide forum
of floral and fauna experts representing universities, government
departments and various others institutions.
</P>
<P>
The study aims to evaluate the degree of threat as well as
initiate proper conservation strategies for their long-term
survival in Sri Lanka, known for its richness in exotic flora and
fauna.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, 50 percent of fresh water fish, 61
percent of amphibians, 55 percent of reptiles, 27 percent of birds
and 39 percent of mammals are threatened with extinction in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 117 species of land snails including 50 percent of
endemic species, 15 species of fresh water shrimps, 22 species of
fresh water crabs, 70 species of dragonflies and 76 species of
butterflies are also threatened.
</P>
<P>
In terms of plants, the study said 700 species of flowering
plants are under threat of extinction.
</P>
<P>
"These figures are all the more significant as they are not
exhaustive. Only a mere 1,239 species of fauna and only 811
species of flowering plants have been evaluated for threat
status," the IUCN study said.
</P>
<P>
There wasn't enough data to even consider evaluating many of
the other species, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0321 </DOCNO>
