<HEADLINE> U.S. Will Not Fight in Colombia: Brazilian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President
Fernando Enrique Cardoso said Monday that he was reassured by the
U.S. government that the United States would not take any military
action in Colombia to fight drug cartels there.
</P>
<P>
"Brazil's policy is very clear: we believe it is an internal
affair of Colombia," the President said of the current anti-drug
warfare in Colombia in an interview with the local television.
</P>
<P>
The interview was given during the visit of Barry McCaffrey,
the top U.S. official in charge of anti-drug affairs in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Brazil has to date not received any request for military
assistance from Colombia in its battle against drug bastions, said
Cardoso, adding that his country is willing to provide any kind of
cooperation once Bogota asks for it.
</P>
<P>
According to the President, Brazil has enhanced vigilance along
its border with Colombia to make sure that war conflicts in
Colombia will not spread to the Brazilian territory. Apart from
drug traffickers, the Colombian government is also waging a war
against rebel guerrilla forces.
</P>
<P>
Recent press reports said that the Brazilian government is
preparing a major operation to cut off the traffic along the
Amazon River, which will be conducted by federal police and armed
forces units. The river is a major transportation line for both
the Colombian guerrillas and drug traffickers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
