<HEADLINE> Second Round of World Chess Championship Ends in Draw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The second round of the
International Chess Federation (FIDE) world chess championship
ended in a draw in Las Vegas on Monday, leaving Russian Alexandre
Khalifman with 1.5 points and Armenian Vladimir Akopian with 0.5.
</P>
<P>
Khalifman, ranking 45th, won the first round in 57 moves on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The match is to last six games, with the winner being the first
to reach 3.5 points. Each victory is worth one point while a draw
is worth half a point.
</P>
<P>
A third round is set for Wednesday, with Akopian, A former
junior world chess champion and ranked 36th, playing the whites.
</P>
<P>
The winner will succeed Russian Anatoly Karpov, who held the
FIDE title from 1975-1985 and since 1993, until he boycotted the
current championship games because of a disagreement with FIDE.
</P>
<P>
The championship games began on July 31. the organizer, has
three million dollars in prize money to be split among the players.
</P>
</TEXT>
