<HEADLINE> ASEAN NTO Meeting Opens in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The 10th meeting of National
Tourism Organizations (NTO) of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) began here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, hosted by Myanmar for the first time, is
 being attended by senior officials of ASEAN member nations,
officials of the ministries related to tourism and entrepreneurs
from private hotels and tourism in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will lay out a series of projects for executing
Visit ASEAN millennium Year 2000 (VAY 2000) as well as planning
the preparations for the ASEAN Tourism Forum 2000 to be held in
Bangkok in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the meeting will also cover issues related to
improving facilitation, investment promotion, manpower training,
the development of an ASEAN tourism website and improving airline
linkages.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, a total of 292,282 foreign
tourists visited Myanmar in the fiscal year 1998-99 which ended in
March. Tourists from other ASEAN member nations accounted for 5
percent of the figures.
</P>
<P>
Tourism-related revenues from hotels, tourism services, banks
and visa fees are about 63 million U.S. dollars annually,
according to the Myanmar Hotels and Tourism Ministry.
</P>
<P>
There are now one foreign company, 12 joint ventures and 508
local private companies running tourism services in the country.
</P>
<P>
There were 21 foreign-invested hotels and 439 local-invested
motels, hotels and inns at the end of April this year with foreign
investment in 29 related projects amounting to 1.1 billion U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dini: NATO's Involvement in Kosovo War Not a Rule For The Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 23 (Xinhua) -- In referring to NATO's decision to
unleash war in Kosovo against Yugoslavia without the approval of
the United Nations, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said
Monday that NATO's self-investiture during the war could not
become a rule for the future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting on Friendship Among the Peoples held in
Italy's resort town of Rimini, Dini said, "The U.S. itself should
be more clear of what it can and cannot do."
</P>
<P>
He said the defense of a right should be separated from "
hegemonic aspirations" in the future and that no more "new
missions" should be undertaken by NATO now that it is without its
"enemy of yesterday."
</P>
<P>
However, Dini made it clear that he was not questioning his
country's friendship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The issue, he said, is to "build a peace which is not solely
American, even if it will continue to have the United States as an
indispensable power."
</P>
<P>
Dini admitted that the U.S. role in the Balkans stemmed from
the EU's weakness "as a political entity and its non-existence in
military terms," but, he argued, the U.S. role can be contained by
building up the EU's joint security and foreign policy, by its
enlargement to neighboring countries, including the Balkans, and
by improving international legal instruments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
