<HEADLINE> Comets Guard Cynthia Cooper Named WNBA Player of the Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Houston Comets guard Cynthia
Cooper, who hopes to lead her team to a third straight league
championship, today was named WNBA Player of the Week for the
period ending Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two-time league MVP averaged 28.3 points and 6.7 assists in
three games to win the award for the second time this season. She
also shot 28-of-29 from the foul line as the Western Conference
champions ended the regular season with a 26-6 record.
</P>
<P>
Cooper scored a season-high 42 points in an 80-71 victory over
the Utah Starzz on August 16 and handed out a career-high 10
assists in Saturday's 74-65 win over the Sacramento Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
She sat out Firday's 68-64 loss to the Los Angeles Sparks,
mourning the loss of teammate Kim Perrot, who died of cancer on
Thursday. Today, Cooper joined teammates in memorial services for
Perrot in Houston.
</P>
<P>
Cooper paced the WNBA in scoring for the third straight year at
22.0 points per game and finished fifth in assists, averaging 5.1
per contest.
</P>
<P>
Houston earned a bye in the first round of the playoffs and
will face the Sacramento-Los Angeles winner in the Western
Conference Finals beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Others nominated for the final regular-season award were
Detroit's Wendy Palmer, Lisa Leslie of the Sparks, Orlando's Taj
McWilliams, Phoenix's Jennifer Gillom and Sacramento's Tangela
Smith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. High-tech Plants Register Faster Productivity Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 23 (Xinhua) -- High-tech manufacturing
plants in the United States registered significantly faster
productivity growth than plants in other industries, according to
a study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The average plant in high-tech industries, which include
electric machinery, scientific instruments and chemicals, posted
productivity gains of 3.3 percent between 1963 and 1992, the last
year for which official data is available. That compares with
average productivity increase of 2.5 percent for all manufacturing
industries.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the Conference Board, a leading U.S.
business membership and research organization, covered virtually
all of America's manufacturing plants that report data to the U.S.
Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Older surviving manufacturing plants in high-tech industries
have showed the highest productivity gains since 1967, according
to the study. The newest high-tech plants, however, tended to be
competitive more quickly than in other industries. But high-tech
status did not guarantee success and some low-tech industries such
as textiles also showed large gains.
</P>
<P>
The study shed new light on the productivity performance of
both start-ups in U.S. manufacturing and long-term survivors.
</P>
<P>
While newer plants with access to adequate capital and the
latest technology have obvious competitive advantages over many
older plants, the study showed that experience is a critical
factor boosting productivity. "Managers cannot entirely avoid the
learning process simply by hiring skilled workers or heavily
investing in new technology," the Conference Board said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
