<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port Expansion Project Begins in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Work on the second-phase
expansion project of Zhapu Port, an emerging sea port in east
China's Zhejiang Province, has started, as part of the national
effort to establish the Shanghai International Shipping Center.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will involve a total investment of 746
million yuan (90.2 million U.S. dollars), aims to build a 15,000-
dwt berth for sundry goods, a 15,000-dwt multi-purpose berth, a 20,
000-dwt coal dock, and an array of inland supporting facilities in
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Zhapu, which is near Shanghai, has 70 km. of coastline with a
depth of 10 to 15 m., and is generally considered a good deep-
water port. It now has seven berths.
</P>
<P>
Zhapu is expected to have a total cargo handling capacity of 30
million tons by the year 2000 and 50 million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Customs offices, inspection offices, commodity checks, and
quarantine monitors, have been established to the port since its
approval by the State Council in 1996 as a first-class open port.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
