<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Attributes Attack Against Colombian Consulate to Secret Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 23 (Xinhua)-- The Venezuelan government on
Monday attributed a bomb attack against Colombia's consulate to a
local clandestine group.
</P>
<P>
Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel attributed the
attack at 3:30 a.m. local time to a clandestine group called the "
Tupamaro Movement," which is protesting the military trial of four
Venezuelans in Colombia's capital of Santa Fe de Bogota, and the
killing of other Venezuelans in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The explosion shattered windows and destroyed the main door of
the consulate's building without causing injuries to victims.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan government ordered police to strengthen
vigilance around the consulate, the Colombian Embassy and the
Colombo-Venezuela Institute in Caracas.
</P>
<P>
According to police at the Colombian-Venezuelan Institute in
Caracas, where an explosive device was defused on Monday, police
found pamphlets from the Tupamaro Movement.
</P>
<P>
The secret organization was set up in 1998 under the flag of
murdering corrupt officials and policemen in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Rangel denied the attacks were related to the political
disagreements between Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez and his
Colombian counterpart Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's General Consul in Venezuela, Jose Alfredo Maestre,
dismissed rumors on Monday that the attack and other events would
upset relations between both countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
