<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Officials Allegedly Involved in Bank Bali Scandal Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The independent Indonesian
Corruption Watch (ICW) Monday disclosed that 11 high-ranking
officials were allegedly involved in the Bank Bali scandal,
according to The Indonesian Observer.
</P>
<P>
The 11 people named by the corruption watchdog in its report
include President B.J. Habibie's chief adviser A.A. Baramuli,
Finance Minister Bambang Subianto, State Enterprises Minister
Tanri Abeng, former State Auditor chief as well as ex-commissioner
of Bank Bali J.B. Sumarlin, Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency
(IBRA) chairman Glenn Yusuf, IBRA deputy chairmen Pande Lubis and
Farid Harianto.
</P>
<P>
The ICW has accused businessman Djoko Chandra of transferring
200 billion rupiah (28.5 million U.S. dollars) to the so-called
"Habibie Success Team" through the account of his wife Anna
Bontaran. The so-called "Habibie Success Team" aims to secure the
"re-election" of the incumbent president, who is the ruling Golkar
Party's presidential candidate, in the November presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
ICW Coordinator Teten Masduki said the ICW has hard evidence of
the close relationship between Minister Tanri and Setya Novanto,
deputy treasurer of Golkar who is one of the key players in the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
Certain parties have pressed Bank Bali ex-president Rudy Ramli
to reveal the scandal in plain terms, "and not touching upon the
political nuances," Teten was quoted by The Indonesian Observer
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Election winner Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle said
last week that it has hard evidence showing the direct involvement
of 16 people in the scam: four ministerial-level executives, three
high-ranking officials, two political party functionaries, five
business tycoons, one confidante of the president and one brother
of the head of state.
</P>
<P>
The Bank Bali saga began when a top official of the Golkar
colluded with high ranking officials to help Bank Bali collect
interbank loans totaling 904 billion rupiah (about 129 million
U.S. dollars) from a liquidated bank at a huge fee of 546 billion
rupiah (78 million dollars), although under the recapitalization
scheme, the government fully guarantees interbank borrowings.
</P>
</TEXT>
