<HEADLINE> Urgent: China's Legislature Opens New Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature, the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, opened its
new week-long session here today, to review nine legislative bills.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Committee, presided over today's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to the session's agenda, a draft amendment to the
Personal Income Tax Law, proposed by the State Council and to be
tabled at today's meeting, will be put for vote when the session
concludes next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The only amendment to be made to the law is to delete the words
"bank interest" from the items listed for exemption of personal
income tax.
</P>
<P>
Another bill put forward by the State Council proposes an
increase of national debt for fixed-asset investment and an
adjustment to central government budget. It will be explained to
the lawmakers on Saturday and subject to vote next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the government said these two pieces of
legislation are intended to stimulate consumption and invigorate
the slack market demand. 
</P>
