<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Record Holder Barmasai Beaten in Men's Steeplechase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- World record holder Bernard
Barmasai suffered a surprise defeat in the men's steeplechase as
his fellow Kenyan Christopher Koskei grabbed the title at the 7th
World Athletics Championships here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai, who set the world record of seven minutes 55.72
seconds on August 24, 1997, finished a distance fifth place in 8:
13.51.
</P>
<P>
Koskei, 25, who ran barefoot to win the silver in the 1995
World Championships, stormed to victory in 8:11.76, with another
Kenyan and defending champion Wilson Boit Kipketer second in 8:12.
09.
</P>
<P>
The bronze was won by Ali Ezzine of Morocco Paul Kosgei with a
time of 8:12.73. Paul Kosgei, also of Kenya, finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
"We had a pre-race plan, " Koskei said. "I mean all four
Kenyans were to work together as a team until 200 meters from the
finish and then it was every man for himself."
</P>
<P>
He added: "As the final 200m point came close I was aware that
both Barmasai and the a German were close by. I know their
strength was very strong. But I collected my thoughts mentally and
concentrated on the finish line. The result you know."
</P>
<P>
Kipketer said: "I fell very good because I didn't expect to be
in top three since I haven't had a very good season. I had an
injury in 1997 in my achilles tendor. "
</P>
<P>
But the 1-2 finish failed to live up to the expectation of the
Kenyans, who clean-swept all the three medals in the last
championships with Kipketer winning the gold, three-time world
champion Moses Kiptanui at second and Barmasai third.
</P>
<P>
"It was a shame not to achieve a clean sweep," said Kipketer. "
That's what we came here for. The heat really didn't affect my
performance. In fact I like to run when it is hot. "
</P>
<P>
But he hoped to come back one day to Seville to break the world
record.
</P>
<P>
"The stadium is fantastic. I hope to come back next year to
break the world record."
</P>
<P>
Barmasai, who has domainated the event since 1997, led the race
from a short time but faded in the late stage.
</P>
<P>
The race was somewhat a repeat of the fifth stage of the Golden
League in Zurich two weeks ago except that the result was
different.
</P>
<P>
The world record holder revealed that he had Koskei to let him
win in Zurich as he was overtaken by the teammate at the end of
the race.
</P>
<P>
The victory kept Barmasai, who had won the previous four stages
in the Golden League, in the chase for the season-ending one
million U.S. dollars jackpot.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF has decided to investigate the case but Kosei later
denied there was a deal between them.
</P>
<P>
The four Kenyans then jogged a victory lap holding their
national colors and was greeted by a boisterous crowd of 40,000.
</P>
<P>
Ezzine said: "I am very proud of my bronze because no other
Moroccan has ever got a medal in steeplechase." 
</P>
</TEXT>
