<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Bodybuilders to Take Part in Asian Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will send eight
bodybuilders to the Asian Bodybuilding Championships which will
begin Thursday in Chinese Taipei, according to Bernama news agency
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Bodybuilding Federation (MBBF) decided to send a full
team after the National Sports Council (NSC) agreed to pay for the
trip, MBBF executive secretary Francis Yong told Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The eight were the champions of the respective categories at
the national championships held in Malacca two weeks ago, he said,
adding they are Mohamed Ali Sukardi (flyweight), Sazali Abdul
Samad (bantamweight), Abdul Ghani Abdul Kadir (lightweight), Syed
Fazli Syed Ali (welterweight), Liaw Teck Leong (light middleweight)
, Othman Yahya (middleweight), Wong Ngai Heong (light heavyweight)
and Terry Gallyot (heavyweight).
</P>
<P>
Yong said although the competition would be tough, the exposure
and experience would be useful as the bodybuilders geared
themselves for the biennial SEA (South East Asia) Games in 2001,
which Malaysia will host.
</P>
<P>
The team's chief coach Abdul Aziz Ahmad is optimistic that the
Malaysians would be able to win two golds, two silvers and a
bronze at the Asian meet. Sazali and Wong were tipped to win the
gold medals at stake in the bantamweight and light heavyweight
respectively while Liaw and Gallyot were expected to walk away
with the silver medals and Syed Fazli should win the bronze in the
welter weight category.
</P>
<P>
At the Asian meet in Vietnam last year, Sazali won the gold
medal in the bantamweight category while the two silvers came from
Zetri Munir (bantamweight) and Liaw (light middleweight).
</P>
<P>
The bodybuilders will leave for Taipei on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
