<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, August 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Interim Administrative Mission in
Kosovo (UNMIK) Monday announced that UNMIK police had started
taking over primary responsibility for law and order in Pristina,
capital of the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the U.N. spokesman, told a press
conference here that the police assumed investigative authority
and jurisdiction for enforcing criminal codes, conducting
investigations, making arrests for criminal offense and
interfacing with the community. (UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Monday
asked for an all-out review of the contracts holds in the oil-for-
food program as they pose "serious implications" for the
humanitarian program in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council on the implementation of
the new 180 day phase of the oil-for-food program beginning May 25,
Annan expressed concern about the number of contracts currently on
hold, worth some 500 million U.S. dollars. (UN-Iraq-Oil-For-Food)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABUJA -- Seven foreign ministers of the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS) would hold a one-day meeting in Lome,
Togo's capital, Thursday to discuss the insurgency in northern
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
A statement published Monday by the secretariat of the 16-
member organization said ministers from Cote d'Ivoire, Ghana,
Guinea, Liberia, Nigeria, Sierra Leone and Togo would attend the
meeting. (ECOWS-Liberian Conflict)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British and Irish Governments have insisted they
are at one on the peace process in Northern Ireland, despite
disagreeing in public over the IRA (Irish Republican Army) cease-
fire.
</P>
<P>
Irish Foreign Minister David Andrews told reporters on Monday
that "in the round," he and Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary
of State, Mo Mowlam, had agreed the cease-fire was intact. (UK-N.
Ireland)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has decided
to appoint Tom Koenigs of Germany as a deputy special
representative for the United Nations Interim Administrative
Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK), a U.N. statement said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Koenigs, who will be in charge of civil administration in UNMIK,
will replace Dominique Vian of France, who "will be returning to
his duties with the French Government," said the statement issued
by the U.N. spokesman. (UN-Kosovo-Appointment)
