<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Montalvo Wins Women's Long Jump in Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Niurka Montalvo claimed the
first gold medal for host Spain at the World Athletics
Championships when she won the women's long jump in foul dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Spaniard, 32, flied 7.06 meters in her final jump, which
defeated her nearest opponent Fiona May of Italy into the second
place by 0.12 meters.
</P>
<P>
Marion Jones of the United States, who aimed to take four gold
medals including the long jump, only managed to finish third at 6.
83 meters.
</P>
<P>
However, Montalvo's final attempt had caused a row which May
claimed that it was no jump for the Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
"It was obviously a foul, you can watch the replay," angry May
said.
</P>
<P>
Televison replay showed that Montalvo's right foot crossed
about two centimeters over the line on the jumping pad.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot say I'm happy and I don't want to be unsporting but
everybody saw what happened in Montalvo's last jump. I am showing
good sportsmanship and settle for this. It is not my job to make
a protest, it is my team which does this," she added.
</P>
<P>
According to reliable sources, the Italian team has appealed
against the decision and a rule is expected tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Montalvo insisted that she had a good jump in the
final round and told May to learn to lose.
</P>
<P>
"You have to learn to lose in the competition," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Normally I'm good with my last attempt and tonight proved this
fact. My last attempt was clearly valid. The take-off board
showed no mark to indicate a foul, so I believe it was good,"
added the joyful Montalvo.
</P>
<P>
After five rounds of the competition, May led a field of 12
jumpers with 6.94 meters from the third attempt while Montalvo was
second at 6.88, which came from her third try.
</P>
<P>
Montalvo, who was first to appear in the order, made the
victorious jump in the sixth round while May only made it at 6.87
meters.
</P>
<P>
For Jones, it was a disappointing jump tonight. When entering
into the field, Jones had been the top favourite to win with
personal best of 7.31 meters.
</P>
<P>
"Of course I am a little bit disappointed. I came here to win,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"This time it didn't go my way but that means I just have to
try next year again," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990824.0370 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Finshes 1-2 in Steeplechase, Jones Fails to Win Gold Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan displayed their dominance
in the 3,000 meters steeplechase as Christopher Koskei led a 1-2
finish on Monday at the 7th World Athletics Championships, but
women's super star Marion Jones had her dream of winning four gold
medals dashed, only settling for a bronze in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
Koskei, 25, who ran barefoot to win the silver in the 1995
World Championships, stormed to victory in 8:11.76, with another
Kenyan and defending champion Wilson Boit Kipketer second in 8:12.
09. The third place went to Ali Ezzine of Morocco with a time of 8:
12.73.
</P>
<P>
But Kenya's world record holder Bernard Barmasai suffered a
surprise defeat, finished a distance fifth in 8:13.51. Paul Kosgei,
also of Kenya, finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
"We had a pre-race plan, " Koskei said. "I mean all four
Kenyans were to work together as a team until 200 meters from the
finish and then it was every man for himself."
</P>
<P>
He added: "As the final 200m point came close I was aware that
both Barmasai and the a German were close by. I know their
strength was very strong. But I collected my thoughts and
concentrated on the finish line. The result you know."
</P>
<P>
Kipketer said: "I fell very good because I didn't expect to be
in top three since I haven't had a very good season. I had an
injury in 1997 in my achilles tendor. "
</P>
<P>
Jones, who retained her 100 meters world title on Sunday and
also aimed to win the long jump, 200m and 1600m relay, had to
reduce her four-medal hope to three when she only won a bronze
with a jump of 6.83 meters.
</P>
<P>
"Of course I am a little disappointed, I came here to win. This
time it didn't go my way but that means I just have to try next
year again."
</P>
<P>
Local jumper Niurka Montalvo soared to victory with a jump of 7.
06 meters in her last attempt. Italian Fiona May, gold medallist
in the 1995 World Championships, led the field of 12 jumpers with
6.94 meters until Montalvo registered the last winning efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Normally I'm good with my last attempt in competition and
tonight proved this fact," she said. "My last attempt was clearly
valid. The take-off board shows no mark to indicate a foul, so I
believe it was good."
</P>
<P>
But the Italian delegation appealed the decision alleging
Montalvo had overstepped the take-off board in her last attempt.
</P>
<P>
"It was obviously a foul," said May. "You can watch the replay.
"
</P>
<P>
The organizers said a decision was expected to be made tonight.
</P>
<P>
The 1-2 finish in the steeplechase failed to live up to the
expectation of the Kenyans, who clean-swept all the three medals
in the last championships with Kipketer winning the gold, three-
time world champion Moses Kiptanui at second and Barmasai third.
</P>
<P>
"It was a shame not to achieve a clean sweep," said Kipketer. "
That's what we came here for. The heat really didn't affect my
performance. In fact I like to run when it is hot. "
</P>
<P>
But he hoped to come back one day to Seville to break the world
record.
</P>
<P>
"The stadium is fantastic. I hope to come back next year to
break the world record."
</P>
<P>
The day's first gold medal went to German's European champion
Franka Dietzsch, who won the women's discus throw with a toss of
68.14 meters.
</P>
<P>
Anastasia Kelesidou of Greece took the silver in 66.05 meters
and Romania's Nicoleta Grasu third in 65.35.
</P>
<P>
"I came here as the second best in the world so far this year
and I thought I would be satisfied even if I only got the bronze,"
Dietzsch said. "Now I have two major golds. I have no dreams for
the future, next year is next year."
</P>
<P>
In the men's high jump final, Vyacheslav Voronin of Russia,
cleared 2.37 meters for the gold, improving his personal best of 2.
36.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Mark Boswell finished second by jumping over 2.35
meters and Martin Buss of German settled for the third in 2.32.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Charles Austin, who had a personal best of 2.
40 meters and the hot favorite with the absence of world record
holder Javier Sotomayor of Cuba, wound up only eighth with 2.29.
</P>
<P>
"I controled myself today," Voronin said. "My body and mind
were in harmony. These great championships are all about your
psychological strength. We all train to the same level, the mind
is what decides the medals."
</P>
<P>
World men's triple jump record holder Honathan Edwards of
Britain passed the first hurdle comfortably with a jump of 17.28
meters in the heat. Only Bulgarian Rostislav Dimitrov's 17.30 was
superior to his.
</P>
<P>
Michael Johnson and Colin Jackson also eased into to the semi-
finals in the 400 meters and 110 meters hurdle respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
