<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke082401-Pak Always Desires Tension-Free Ties with India: Sajjad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Pakistan's Senate
Wasim Sajjad Monday called on the international community to
persuade India to resume dialogue with Pakistan to resolve all
outstanding issues, especially the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad was talking to a nine-member delegation of British
parliamentarians which is paying a week-long visit to Pakistan,
official sources said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Kashmir should be the cause for greater concern to
the international community in view of the consistent and massive
violations of human rights by over 700,000 Indian security forces
stationed in the Indian-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has always desired tension-free and mutually
beneficial relations with India and to achieve that end it remains
committed to a substantive and result-oriented dialogue with India
aimed at finding an amicable solution to all issues, including
Kashmir, said the Senate chairman.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad said Pakistan's commitment to the dialogue process was
evident from the measures it has taken to promote a conducive
atmosphere in South Asia, including commencement of bus service
between India and Pakistan, release of Indian fishermen and
renewal of sports exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad asserted that India should reciprocate Pakistan's
gestures by translating its commitments into reality and engage in
substantive talks to resolve the Kashmir issue on the basis of the
wishes of the Kashmiri people.
</P>
<P>
He assured the British Parliamentarians that Pakistan remained
committed to avoiding a nuclear and conventional arms race in the
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this objective Pakistan had proposed a strategic
restraint regime which, he said, has been rejected by India.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the British Parliamentary delegation, John
Wilkinson, underscored the need for resolving all outstanding
disputes between India and Pakistan, including Kashmir, through
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kashmir issue was an unfinished item of the
agenda of the Sub-Continent's partition and that as a result of
that there has been tremendous suffering.
</P>
<P>
He opined that the resolution of the Kashmir issue would lead
to the economic betterment of the people of both India and
Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
