<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Moves to Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average moved sharply to the record high Monday one day before the
Federal Reserve was expected to raise interest rates in a bid to
preempt inflation from the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip index closed up 199.15 at 11,299.76. surpassing
the record closing high of 11,209.84 set on July 16. The Dow rose
136.72 points in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 23.61 at 1,360.22 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 71.24 at 2,719.57.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied despite the predication for hike in interest
rates at the Federal Reserve policymakers' meeting in Washington
Tuesday. The Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned
earlier that the Federal Reserve would act "promptly and
forcefully" to raise the rates if the new data show pressures on
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The stocks have faltered after the warning but edged back last
week as investors absorbed the likelihood of higher rates.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 8.72 at 634.81 and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 4.72 at 792.51. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.87 at 437.25.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,723 up, 1,269 down and 550
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 673.76 million shares from 658.10
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
