<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Urges Brazil to Accelerate Structural Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) said on Monday that the developments of Brazilian
economy in the first half of this year were significantly better
than expected, but urged the government to accelerate structural
reforms to lay foundations for sustained recovery.
</P>
<P>
"Developments in the Brazilian economy during the first half of
1999 have been, on the whole, significantly better than expected
under the revised IMF-supported program that was approved by the
executive board at the end of March 1999," the IMF said in an
annual review of the Brazilian economy.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's real gross domestic product (GDP), which had stagnated
in 1998, partly due to the adverse impact of the Asian and Russian
crisis, began to recover and grew at annualized rates of 3.2
percent and 3.8 percent in the first and second quarters of 1999
respectively, relative to the preceding quarters.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year of 1999, the IMF projected real GDP to
decline by 1 percent or less, compared with the decline of almost
4 percent projected in the revised March program.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price inflation in the first seven months of 1999
remained around 5 percent, reflecting the initial overshooting of
the exchange rate of the Brazilian real after it was allowed to
float in January was corrected relatively quickly. For the year as
a whole, the consumer price is expected to increase by 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said the authorities' commitment to the policy
framework of the program, along with the strong official
international support and the constructive voluntary involvement
of the private sector, had been instrumental in securing an early
recovery of confidence, correcting the initial overshooting of the
exchange rate, and allowing an incipient pick up in activity with
relatively low inflation.
</P>
<P>
However, it stressed that, to lay the foundation for sustained
recovery, the authorities' principal challenges are to build on
the progress already achieved in implementing fiscal consolidation
and to accelerate structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
"Directors urged the authorities to continue monitoring fiscal
developments closely, and to stand ready to take further measures
as needed to ensure that the targeted public sector primary
surplus of 3.1 percent of GDP is strictly adhered to," the IMF
said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF stressed that fiscal sustainability over the medium
term depends heavily on the progress in pending structural fiscal
reforms, especially regarding the social security and tax systems,
and in the implementation of administrative reform.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, they (directors) strongly urged the authorities to
intensify their efforts to ensure early and substantial progress
in these areas," the IMF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
